<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LongLost     05-28 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Long Lost,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Pleads Innocent to Stealing Teen-ager Missing for Four Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICTORVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 40-year-old man pleaded innocent
Friday to a felony child-stealing charge after a search turned up a
teen-age boy who had been missing for nearly four years, officials
said.
   Patrick Michael McCleery was arrested Wednesday after
Christopher Elias, 17, was discovered in McCleery's trailer in
Apple Valley, a town about 85 miles northeast of Los Angeles.
   Elias was 13 when he disappeared in July 1984 from a recreation
area in Lake County, about 100 miles north of San Francisco.
   The teen-ager was reunited with his parents Thursday at the
sheriff's station at Victorville, six miles west of Apple Valley,
and the family headed back to their home at Clear Lake.
   Detective Dale Sharp said McCleery was living in a trailer in
1984 near Clear Lake, where the teen-ager's father manages a
marina. ``One day, McCleery rented a boat from them, and that was
the last they saw of him or their son,'' Sharp said.
   The boy's mother said the only contact the family had with the
boy was one telephone call a year in which he would say, ``I'm
alive,'' and hang up. On Wednesday the mother said she received an
anonymous call from someone who gave her an Apple Valley phone
number to reach her son, Sharp said.
   The number was wrong but detectives canvassed telephone
customers with the same prefix, Sharp said, and the boy was found
in the camping trailer McCleery used as a home.
   McCleery originally was arrested for investigation of
kidnapping, but Deputy District Attorney Gary Fagan said
child-stealing was the ``appropriate'' charge.
   Kidnapping involves an element of force while child-stealing
involves enticement and concealment, he said. A hearing has been
scheduled for May 31 where McCleery may face additional charges.
</TEXT>
