<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BridgeAccident     05-28 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bridge Accident,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Workers Hurt In Williamsburg Bridge Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four iron workers fell 30 feet when a scaffold
on the newly reopened Williamsburg Bridge collapsed Friday
afternoon, and one was hospitalized in serious condition,
authorities said.
   The four men suffered leg, neck, back and ankle injuries, said
Peter O'Donnell, a police spokesman.
   James Molin, 23, of Queens, was in serious but stable condition
with multiple fractures, said Bellevue Hospital Center spokesman
Peter Schectman. The others were evaluated in the emergency room,
he said.
   The accident occurred around 4:20 p.m. on the Brooklyn side of
the span, under elevated railroad tracks that lead onto the bridge
that links the borough to Manhattan, said Victor Ross, spokesman
for the Department of Transportation.
   The workers, employed by Gottlieb Ironworks, of Queens, landed
on metal plates 60 to 80 feet above the ground that catch debris
from trains, Ross said.
   The bridge reopened for restricted, one-way traffic Thursday
after a six-week shutdown for structural deterioration.
   Schwartz said two wooden ``needle beams'' that support the
scaffolding planks the workers stand on cracked. Police removed the
scaffolding and were investigating the collapse, Ross said.
</TEXT>
