<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-PanamaPoll     05-28 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama Poll,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll: Majority of Americans Disapprove Of Reagan's Panama Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public support has plummeted for President
Reagan's handling of developments in Panama, where the
administration is seeking to oust military ruler Manuel Antonio
Noriega, according to poll results published Friday.
   The Washington Post-ABC News poll found that 58 percent of
Americans disapproved of the way Reagan has handled the situation
in Panama, while 26 percent approved and 16 percent were undecided,
the newspaper reported in Saturday editions.
   A similar poll conducted March 21 found 39 percent of the public
critical of the administration and 49 percent supporting its Panama
policies.
   The most recent survey of 1,328 adults was conducted May 20-25,
ending just as Secretary of State George P. Shultz announced that
negotiations aimed at Noriega's ouster had collapsed.
   The poll found that 44 percent of Republicans disapproved of
Reagan's Panama policy, while 40 percent approved. Among Democrats
and independents, six out of 10 disapproved of the way the
president has handled the situation.
   The poll had a margin of error or plus or minus 3 percentage
points.
</TEXT>
