<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 0109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Panama Bjt   05-28 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, Bjt,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abrams Describes New Negotiating Strategy on Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is working on a new strategy
for dealing with Panama that would involve a ``four-sided'' effort
to oust military leader Manuel Antonio Noriega, Assistant Secretary
of State Elliott Abrams says.
   Abrams discussed the proposed effort in a telephone interview
Friday as intense diplomatic contacts continued following the
collapse on Wednesday of direct U.S. negotiations with Panama.
   One official, who asked not to be identified, said that some
members of Congress are so eager for a solution in Panama that they
are recommending that the administration authorize Noriega's
assassination.
   Assassination of foreign leaders is forbidden under a 1981
executive order.
   Abrams said the new initiative would involve discussions among
officials from the United States, Latin American democracies, the
Panamanian government and the opposition.
   ``What many Latins have in mind is seeing if they can negotiate
a complete package deal and seeing if they can get Noriega and the
United States to go along,'' Abrams said.
   He said Noriega would more likely accept a negotiated solution
if the Latin American democracies can work together to isolate him
diplomatically.
   Abrams acknowledged the task won't be easy because of the strong
sentiment in the hemisphere in support of non-interventionism.
Weighing against that sentiment, he said, ``is the growing support
in the hemisphere for human rights and democracy and the war on
drugs.''
   Two federal grand juries in Florida indicted Noriega in February
on drug smuggling charges.
   Abrams said he does not believe that any Latin American
initiative can work unless the United States plays a role as well.
   Among the countries most receptive to the idea of a Latin
American initiative in Panama are Guatemala and Venezuela, he said.
   Abrams met Friday morning with former Venezuelan President
Carlos Andres Perez, who is seeking election this year to a new
term and had expressed interest previously in contributing to a
settlement in Panama.
   ``This is a situation we cannot allow to continue adrift,''
Perez said.
   Abrams said Guatemalan President Vinicio Cerezo has offered to
host talks between Noriega and the Panamanian opposition, with
Guatemalan officials serving as witnesses.
   This proposal has been endorsed by ousted Panamanian President
Eric Arturo Delvalle, whom the United States continues to recognize
as the legitimate authority in Panama.
   While expressing support for a multilateral approach, Abrams
said it is essential that diplomatic and economic pressure on
Noriega be maintained as well.
   Otherwise, the negotiations would amount to nothing more than
``sweet talk,'' he said.
   As part of the U.S. plan to restore democratic rule in Panama
next year, Noriega was to step down this August and go into
temporary exile. In return, the federal drug smuggling indictments
were to be dismissed.
   But Noriega rejected the proposal and the talks were called off.
   In a speech Friday, Noriega blamed Abrams and U.S. Ambassador
Arthur Davis for the breakdown in talks but he didn't elaborate on
the charge. Earlier, he had complained that the United States
presented him with an ultimatum.
   He called for ``foreign forces'' to leave Panama and for the
United States to ``leave Panama in peace. Sirs, for God's sake
leave it in peace.''
   During a photo session in Helsinki on Friday with Finnish
President Mauno Koivisto, President Reagan said he and his advisers
have reached no decision about how to proceed on the Panamanian
problem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
