<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Summit-TV     05-28 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-TV,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sunday TV Talk Shows Focus on Moscow Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit-Reagan Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sunday television talk shows will focus on
the start of the Moscow summit talks that day between President
Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   CBS's ``Face the Nation'' and NBC's ``Meet the Press'' will
originate in the Soviet capital. ABC's ``This Week with David
Brinkley'' will be televised from Washington as usual, although
correspondent Sam Donaldson will participate from Moscow.
   ABC has expanded its program by 30 minutes to 1{ hours and NBC
is expanding its show to one hour.
   The ABC guests include National Security Adviser Colin Powell,
Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennadi Gerasimov, former
National Security Adviser Zbigniew Brzezinski; Richard Perle,
former assistant defense secretary, and former NATO commander Gen.
Bernard Rogers.
   The CBS guests are Secretary of State George Shultz and Soviet
dissident Sergei Grigoryants.
   NBC's guests will be White House chief of staff Howard Baker and
Georgi A. Arbatov, member of the Soviet Communist Party Central
Committee.
   CNN's ``Newsmaker Sunday'' guest is Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci.
   The network evening news shows will originate from Moscow
throughout the five-day summit starting Sunday. The weekday morning
shows will have at least one co-anchor there.
   Dan Rather of CBS and Peter Jennings of ABC began their
broadcasts from the Soviet capital last week. NBC's Tom Brokaw will
begin broadcasting from there on Monday.
   ABC, NBC and CNN plan live coverage of Reagan's arrival in
Moscow on Sunday, beginning at 6 a.m. EDT. CBS will have a report
on the arrival at 9 a.m.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
