<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Politics-Quotes     05-28 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Politics-Quotes,200</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments Friday from the
presidential campaign trail:
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, blasting the Reagan administration for alleged
$200,000 payments by the CIA to Panamanian Gen. Manuel Noriega:
``We've been paying that guy what we pay the president of the
United States. You can't be serious about waging a real war against
drugs when we have an administration that can't say no to Noriega.''
   
   GEORGE BUSH, unfazed by his new underdog status as suggested by
recent polls: ``Do I worry about it? I don't worry about it. I like
fighting back. (Dukakis) is the front-runner. He's been decreed
that in poll after poll. And I like fighting back. I remember
Iowa.''
   
   JESSE JACKSON, hearkening back to the beginning of his Rainbow
Coalition in his call for people to work together: ``Hispanics in
the barrios, blacks in the ghettos, ranchers on ranches, Indians on
reservations. ... There's a tendency of these people to be
abandoned by law. The real challenge is to begin to pull together
our various backgrounds and find common ground ... to turn to each
other and not on each other.''
</TEXT>
