<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 0131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CelebrityCow Bjt   05-28 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Celebrity Cow, Bjt,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alaska Town's Only Cow Has Celebrity Status</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE CROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAINES, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Where killer whales cruise the harbor,
eagles gather by the thousands, and moose graze next to Main
Street, what takes the title of most exotic animal?
   No contest _ it's Elsie the cow.
   The light brown jersey is bringing fame to Sue Edward's
five-acre farm in Haines, a remote town on the northern end of
Alaska's Inside Passage where residents say they haven't seen a cow
in close to 30 years.
   Second-graders take field trips to see the bovine wonder and her
two bull calves, the summer fair features a contest to guess
Elsie's weight _ 50 cents a chance _ and her ``date'' with an
out-of-town bull made the front page of the local newspaper.
   Edwards, who moved to Haines four years ago from an eastern
Oregon cattle ranch, says she was dismayed to find the fishing town
of some 2,000 people lacked any livestock, aside from a few goats.
   So Elsie was imported last year from a Yukon Territory farm a
few hundred miles away.
   ``I like cows. I'm partial to cows,'' Edwards says.
   ``A lot of people drive new cars and live in cathedral-style
houses. They're in debt up to their ears but they're doing what
they want to do. I've got myself a milk cow and I'm in debt up to
my ears and I'm doing what I want to do.''
   It's not easy living in a one-cow town.
   Take hay, for starters. Prime alfalfa hay sells for up to $18 a
bale on the rare occasions it is shipped to Haines. So Elsie and
her offspring _ 15-month-old Pooh-Da-Bear and the newborn Little Ed
_ have to settle for inferior hay trucked south from the Yukon.
   But it costs $4 a bale, at least four times more than it would
in the lower 48 states, Edwards says.
   Then there are the local moose, who took a keen interest in
Elsie around calving time. They didn't hurt the cow or Little Ed,
born May 6, but struck terror into the heart of Sherman the horse.
   ``The horse and the moose have a grudge match,'' Edwards says.
``The moose'll bugle at the horse. The horse'll start running at
the end of his rope.''
   So far, the horse-moose match has cost Edwards one downed fence
and several trips to recapture the fleeing Sherman.
   Despite Elsie's popularity, no one else in town has been
inspired to buy a cow.
   ``There's not a lot of encouragement around. There's definitely
more skepticism,'' Edwards says. She fits in farming while selling
gear at the local cannery with help from her husband, David, a
logger.
   Still, local folks who take Alaska's bald eagles, whales and
other abundant wildlife for granted have come to count on Elsie and
the Edwards' barnyard antics for entertainment.
   It started when Elsie was shipped to Skagway, about an hour
north by state ferry, for a liaison with a bull.
   Stardom struck on the return trip. The cow got rambunctious and
tore open a sack of grain in the back of Edwards' pickup truck,
down on the car deck of the ferry.
   The purser's call for the cow's owner alerted other people to
the rare beast on board, and the ship's cook sent down a special
request for some fresh milk, which he said he had never tasted.
   The empty pail was presented at the dock. Elsie, by that time
looking seasick and none too happy, nonetheless obliged with a few
squirts, Edwards recalls.
   By the time the cow disembarked, a crowd was waiting, people
were cheering, and the editor of the weekly Chilkat Valley News had
a camera at hand. ``That's was the beginning of Elsie's glory,''
Edwards says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
