<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Schiller-Obit     05-28 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Schiller-Obit,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assistant Postmaster General Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herbert H. Schiller, an assistant postmaster
general for technology who helped advance automation and technology
developments in mail delivery, has died.
   Schiller, who was 62, died of cancer on Friday at George
Washington University Hospital.
   A native of Vienna, Austria, Schiller came to the United States
in his youth and worked for the Sperry-Rand Corp. and Harris Corp.
before serving as technical director for International Telephone
and Telegraph Corp. He joined the U.S. Postal Service in 1983.
   Under his direction, the postal service initiated technological
developments in optical scanning and document handling. One of
Schiller's innovations, the automated postal teller, will undergo
customer testing later this year.
   Schiller is also credited with establishing a technological
development advisory board of outside academic and industry
professionals at the postal service, and initiated an annual
advanced technology conference.
   A resident of Fairfax, Va., Schiller was born in Austria and
emigrated to the United States in the 1930s. After serving in the
Army in World War II, Schiller was graduated from Carnegie-Mellon
University and received a masters degree in electrical engineering
from Columbia University.
   He is survived by his wife, Julia, and a daughter, Margaret Ann.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880528-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 0110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama Bjt   05-28 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, Bjt,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ousted President Says Noriega Used Talks to Embarrass U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle
said the United States was tricked into negotiating with Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, who used the talks to cement his position
as Panama's de facto ruler.
   From hiding, Delvalle also said Friday that Noriega exploited
the negotiations on the general's eventual removal from power to
embarrass the Reagan administration.
   He said Washington erred in not bringing Panama's opposition and
the region's democracies in the talks.
   ``I have always thought that (the talks) were a ploy to delay
matters, to give (Noriega) time to strengthen his inner circle
within the Panamanian Defense Forces and at the end, yes, to
ridicule President Reagan and the United States,'' Delvalle said.
   ``I don't think (Noriega) was sincere, and I told the (Reagan)
administration that what happened would happen. That wasn't very
difficult. I told them about three weeks ago,'' he said.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz on Wednesday announced that
talks had collapsed and blamed the failure on Noriega.
   Noriega on Friday blamed U.S. Ambassador Arthur Davis and the
State Department's Elliott Abrams for the breakdown.
   Delvalle spoke with several correspondents Friday at a location
the reporters agreed not to identify. He was ousted by Noriega on
Feb. 26, one day after he tried to fire the general, who heads the
nation's 15,000-strong Defense Forces and is the power behind the
Panamanian presidency.
   The United States continues to recognize Delvalle as Panama's
legitimate president.
   Noriega was indicted in the United States in February on drug
trafficking charges, which he denies.
   ``I am disappointed at the fact that they did not use to their
advantage our knowledge of Noriega,'' Delvalle said, criticizing
the United States for attempting to remove Noriega without help
from other Latin American countries.
   He suggested the United States permit Latin American democracies
to take the lead in mediating the crisis, a move the Reagan
administration is exploring.
   Asked if there were circumstances under which he might renounce
his claim to the presidency, Delvalle responded: ``Why should I?
This is one of the basic factors, respect for the constitution by
the military.
   ``All over Latin American there has been a clear, loud message
that (the military) is below civilian government,'' he said.
   Delvalle warned of a rising threat of street violence if Noriega
remains and the economic crisis, prompted in part by U.S.
sanctions, continues. Millions of dollars in Panamanian assets are
frozen in American banks.
   ``I think we will be facing violence in the near future,''
Delvalle said. ``The people of Panama are getting desperate. We
will see some violent demonstrations here in the next few days or
weeks.''
   In a speech to a women's convention Friday, Noriega said he held
the Reagan administration responsible for his personal safety.
   ``I place responsibility for the life of Manuel Antonio Noriega
with the establishment of the United States. I hold the
establishment responsible for the life of this son of God,''
Noriega said.
   The general did not elaborate on his charges that Davis and
Abrams were responsible for the collapse of the talks.
   But he called for ``foreign forces'' to leave Panama and for the
United States to ``leave Panama in peace. Sirs, for God's sake
leave it in peace.''
   The United States normally maintains about 10,000 troops in
Panama, but sent in an additional 2,000 soldiers since the crisis
over Noriega intensified this year.
   Panama's foreign minister, Jorge Eduardo Ritter, said Friday
that Panama's relations with the United States were ``practically
nonexistent.''
   He said relations were bad ``because the United States maintains
recognition of a government that doesn't exist,'' referring to
Washington's continued endorsement of Delvalle as president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
