<HEAD>Donations Pour in To Repair Vandalism to Vietnam Memorial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veterans organizations and radio stations
around the country have raised more than $60,000 to repair
scratches made by vandals on the Vietnam Veterans Memorial.
   ``People have been exceedingly generous,'' Jan Scruggs, founder
and president of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial Fund, said Friday.
   Scruggs said he was surprised so many people were interested in
contributing money to repair the memorial, which has become the
most heavily visited monument in Washington since it was dedicated
six years ago.
   Three small scratches, including one resembling a swastika, were
found on the V-shaped granite wall last month. A Vermont granite
expert has been studying ways to remove the scratches from the
polished granite, which contains the Americans killed in the
Southeast Asian war.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Veterans Convoy Takes Humanitarian Goods to Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five old trucks and buses carrying food,
medical supplies, clothing and toys are on their way to Nicaragua
as part of a nationwide ``Veterans Peace Convoy.''
   Driven by U.S. veterans, the trucks that left Washington on
Friday will hook up with about 50 other trucks from around the
country on June 5 in Austin, Texas, to form a caravan of donated
humanitarian aid to Nicaragua.
   ``This is a people-to-people project to feed children, not a
government one to feed war,'' said Robert Livesay, a Dorchester,
Mass., veteran who launched a project he said will carry 40 tons of
goods to Nicaragua.
   The various legs of the convoy are going through 40 states, with
stops in 90 cities, Livesay said. Other groups started in Seattle;
Missoula, Mont.; Minneapolis; Dayton, Cleveland and Cincinnati,
Ohio; and Portland, Ore.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Economists Boost Growth Predictions, Still See Recession in 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economists for the nation's top businesses
expect high interest rates to push the country into recession
sometime next year despite their revised forecasts for stronger
growth in 1988.
   The survey found that a majority of the economists, 57.8
percent, believed the lengthy American economic expansion, now in
its sixth year, will end with a recession in 1989.
   At the same time, the survey by the National Association of
Business Economists released Friday showed a substantial boost in
growth estimates for this year compared with a survey done three
months ago.
   However, the economists expressed concerns the rapid growth in
foreign demand for U.S. goods, coupled with continued high consumer
spending in this country, would contribute to inflationary
pressures and prompt the Federal Reserve to step in with higher
interest rates to cool off the economy.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Nixon Says Post-Convention Summit Would Be `Three-Ring Circus'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Nixon says a proposed fifth
Reagan-Gorbachev summit later this year would be meaningless unless
the Democratic and Republican presidential candidates also attend.
   Nixon said that with only five months remaining before the Nov.
8 presidential election, too little time remains for the Reagan
administration to complete an arms control agreement in the
national interest.
   President Reagan, quoted by the German newspaper Die Welt, held
out the possibility of another summit before he departed Wednesday
for talks with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev in Moscow.
   But Nixon wrote in a column for this weekend's editions of the
Sunday Times of London, ``Once the two major parties choose their
tickets for the general election, an incumbent's authority _ in
Soviet eyes _ drops to nil,'' he said.
   ``Any summit after the two conventions will be meaningless
unless both the Republican and Democratic nominees agreed to
attend. In the unlikely event that they did, it would be a
ludicrous three-ring circus,'' he wrote.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Playset and Doll Recalled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission has
ordered the recall of a Sweet Home Shoe House playset and Ice Cream
Doll because they may pose a choking hazard to small children.
   About 6,500 of the Sweet Home Shoe House playsets were sold
across the country, the agency said Friday. It described them as a
plastic house in the shape of a work boot, containing 18 pieces of
dolls and doll furniture. The set sold for about $5 and is labeled
``1984 Jumbos Interne set sold for about $5 and is labeled ``1984
Jumbos International (Hong Kong) Co. No. 698.''
   In addition, about 7,800 of the Ice Cream Doll were sold for
about $3 each, the commission said. These are soft dolls with a
plastic ice cream cone suspended around the neck. They are labeled
``Ice Cream Doll, Made in Hong Kong.''
   No injuries have been reported involving the toys, but both
contain small parts which could pose a choking hazard, the
commission said.
   The toys were recalled by Wisconsin Toy Company Inc. of New
York, the commission said. Consumers needing more information may
call the Safety Commission at 1-800-638-2772.
</TEXT>
