<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua 3rdLd-Writethru a0884 05-28 0897</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0884,0917</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Agree to Discuss Extending Truce; Reject Proposal For
Longer Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with rebels rejecting proposal
to extend the talks past Saturday. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `Felix
Garcia ... EDITS 11th graf pvs to conform.
^By ELOY O. AGUILAR</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebel leaders agreed Friday to discuss
a truce extension proposed by the leftist government and one of the
best-known rebel commanders turned himself in to accept government
amnesty.
   Manuel Espinoza, the presidential spokesman, said ``some
advances had been made'' during the second day of the peace talks.
   The government proposed extending the talks beyond their
scheduled end on Saturday, but Contra leaders rejected the
suggestion, saying an agreement could be reached if the government
truly desires one.
   Alfredo Cesar, head of the rebel delegation, said ``we cannot
stay here longer,'' adding that ``if there is political will on the
part of the Sandinistas an agreement can be signed'' on Saturday.
   Felix Garcia Hernandez, known as Alfa Lima, told reporters
Friday that before he asked for amnesty he commanded more than 400
Contras in the Chontales region.
   He said he met with representatives of the Nicaraguan army
several times during the truce and decided to return because of his
family and because he felt Nicaraguans should stop killing each
other. He turned himself in Wednesday and the Sandinista government
announced it Thursday night.
   Alfa Lima abandoned the rebel force with six of his men and said
Friday he hoped to encourage more of his former comrades to take
advantage of the amnesty.
   ``I am going to try to convince my men to come in. There are
many out there who do not know what they are doing or why they are
fighting,'' said the soft-spoken Alfa Lima, still wearing his
camouflage uniform.
   Alfa Lima's former commander-in-chief, Enrique Bermudez, was in
Managua for the peace talks and said upon hearing of his decision,
``We regret it. He was a field commander with a long record. We
consider him a war casualty.''
   Although they agreed to discuss extending the cease-fire, which
is scheduled to end May 30, the rebels still insist on an agreement
that includes a firm schedule of democratic reforms.
   According to a source at the negotiating table, Defense Minister
Gen. Humberto Ortega, head of the government delegation, told the
session ``it would be difficult to reach an agreement by Saturday
noon, but we are not discarding the possibility of a miracle, like
the miracle at Sapoa.''
   Sapoa, a town on the Costa Rican border, was where the March 23
peace agreement was signed by the Sandinista government and the
U.S.-supported rebels.
   Cesar said there was a ``25 percent chance of an agreement.''
   Rebel spokesman Bosco Matamoros said after Friday's session that
``some political topics had been discussed,'' but added the two
sides still differed on fundamental political issues.
   ``We have different concepts of democracy, different concepts of
human rights, the role of the state in a society and the structure
of a judiciary system,'' he said.
   President Daniel Ortega's government feels a permanent
cease-fire is a necessary first step toward peace. The Contras want
political reforms that would enlarge the opposition's role in a
more pluralistic and democratic society.
   On Thursday, the rebel delegates declared they had come to
Managua only to discuss their own plan, which sets deadlines for
government introduction of reforms. The Sandinistas called the
Contra proposals ``unrealistic,'' but agreed to put them on the
table.
   Government negotiators then offered a plan for electoral reforms
and a cease-fire as a continuation of general agreements reached at
Sapoa for a truce, amnesty, a government dialogue with the
political opposition and eventual integration into the political
life of the rebels and their leaders.
   ``The important thing is not to disappoint the expectations of
the people of Nicaragua,'' said Bayardo Arce, vice coordinator of
the political committee of the Sandinista National Liberation
Front, known by its Spanish initials FSLN.
   Luis Rivas Leiva, adviser to the Contra delegation, said: ``We
are paying a high price in the negotiations. The FSLN does not want
to pay any. They are being very inflexible.''
   At the heart of the disagreement are the definition of
democratization and how to go about it.
   Within five days of an agreement, the Contras demand an end to
the military draft, freedom to supply their forces in the field and
total press freedom, including establishment of private radio and
television stations.
   Within two months, they want measures to guarantee political
pluralism, separation of state powers, curtailment of the powers of
the FSLN, guarantees of the right to strike and reforms in the
judiciary and the electoral system.
   The government has offered to discuss electoral reforms, and
announed an amnesty program and a plan for municipal elections.
   ``They have been doing some things, but those are more form than
substance,'' Rivas Leiva said. ``There are some important matters
that involve guarantees for the return of all our people to the
political life of Nicaragua.
   ``They want a permanent cease-fire. We want at the same time a
political process that would democratize Nicaragua,'' he said.
   Cesar is a former Sandinista financial expert. Bermudez, the
Contras' military commander, was once a colonel in the army of the
late President Anastasio Somoza, whom the Sandinistas overthrew in
July 1979.
</TEXT>
