<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Politics,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Party Vows Nationwide Protests To Protest Alleged
Election Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONCLOVA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition National Action Party
called for nationwide protests today after the state legislature
said the governing party's candidate won a disputed mayoral
election here.
   ``We are implementing a civil disobedience insurgency against
the fraud and this trampling of the democratic system,'' Carlos A.
Paiz Falcon, the National Action candidate, said in a telephone
interview Friday night.
   ``We have called on our supporters across the country to occupy
highways, the international bridges with the United States and
other places on Saturday to condemn the fraud,'' he said.
   Paiz Falcon said Manuel Clouthier, his party's presidential
candidate in the July 6 general elections, would be giving party
activists further ``instructions for civil disobedience.''
   The legislature of the border state of Coahuila announced Friday
that Paiz Falcon lost the May 8 special election by 233 votes to
Benigno Franco Coronado of the Institutional Revolutionary Party
(PRI), the government news agency Notimex reported.
   A special election commission said last weekend that Franco
Colorado had won by 294 votes.
   The opposition party claims Paiz Falcon won the election by 448
votes. He said it has copies of the voting tally and can prove the
results of several precincts were altered.
   More than 23,000 ballots were cast.
   ``They falsified the vote,'' an angry Paiz Falcon said. ``The
PRI was the judge, the Congress, the vote-counters. They supplied
the ballots, the paper, everything. The Congress always says what
the party wants. It was an absolute exoneration of the fraud.''
   The PRI has not lost a presidential or gubernatorial elections
since its founding in 1929.
   In regular elections held last October, the governing party won
the Coahuila gubernatorial race and 37 of 38 mayor's posts at
stake. But the legislature annulled the Monclova results, citing
voting irregulatiries and violence. It called the special elections
for May 8.
   The rival parties have battled for nine years for control of
this steel-producing city of 300,000 people about 200 miles south
of the Texas border at Eagle Pass.
   Its most recent administration was controlled by a bilateral
commission after neither party won the 1984 mayoral race outright.
</TEXT>
