<2ND_LINE>PM-Pacific Lumber,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lumber Company Agrees to Stop Clear-Cutting Ancient Redwoods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lumber company has agreed to stop
clear-cutting ancient redwood stands, but the decision drew mixed
reviews from environmentalists and politicians.
   A state senator attacked both Pacific Lumber Co. and
environmentalists, and called the announcement nothing but ``window
dressing and a diversionary tactic.''
   But two other legislators, including state Assemblyman Dan
Hause, who negotiated with Pacific Lumber, called the agreement an
important breakthrough.
   ``The company is the largest private owner of virgin redwood
left in the world, which is why its return to selective logging
practices is so important,'' said Assemblyman Byron Sher, Assembly
Natural Resources Committee chairman.
   Apparently bowing to protests by environmentalists, Pacific
Lumber, located in Scotia, announced Thursday that it has reversed
its 2-year-old policy of clear-cutting the company's 16,000 acres
of virgin redwoods in Humboldt County.
   The company will return to selective logging in virgin forests
and also agreed to consider selling some of the old-growth stands
to public interest groups.
   John Campbell, executive vice president of Pacific Lumber, said
the company agreed to stop clear-cutting _ removing all trees from
an area _ its oldest trees because of its ``sensitivity'' to
environmental and legislative concerns.
   As the agreement was announced, three protesters with the
radical environmental group Earth First! were in their sixth day of
living on makeshift platforms high in redwood trees on the
company's land. The group is attempting to block construction of a
road through an area of virgin redwoods set for clearing.
   Pacific Lumber was purchased in 1985 by corporate raider Charles
Hurwitz, head of the Maxxam Group.
   State Senate Majority Leader Barry Keene, who has represented
the North Coast timber region for 16 years, called the compromise
only a diversion.
   He called it ``a cosmetic truce between a company whose recent
practices can by only described as rapacious and an urban
environmentalist whose knowledge of silviculture is limited to
Sierra Club bulletins.''
   He also complained that the agreement does not include any offer
from Maxxam to restructure the company's $600 million takeover debt
or to guarantee jobs and sustained timber production into the
future.
   Even before the agreement, the state Department of Forestry had
stopped Pacific Lumber from most old-growth cutting.
   Earth First! spokesman Darryl Cherney called the agreement a
slick ``public relations ploy.'' The agreement affects only about
16,000 acres of Pacific Lumber's 200,000-acre holdings, he said.
   ``And it's not even a binding agreement,'' he said. ``The
company had a legislative and bureaucratic gun to its head; so
they're willing to say anything,'' Cherney said.
</TEXT>
