<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Reporters     05-28 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Reporters,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Reporters Barred From Summit Coverage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three reporters from Radio Free
Europe-Radio Liberty have been denied permission to cover the
superpower summit in Moscow, the stations said.
   All three had been granted Soviet visas, Radio Free Europe said
Friday.
   Bill Mahoney, spokesman for the two sister stations based in
Munich, said the stations have asked the State Department to
protest the decision.
   The stations are privately-operated entities which broadcast
news and music to the Soviet bloc. They are largely funded by the
U.S. government.
   The reporters are Wayne Brown, Tom Bodin and Elizabeth Teague.
Bodin is an American, and Ms. Teague is from Britain. The
citizenship of Brown could not be immediately learned.
   Brown was already in Moscow when he was told he would not be
accredited ``and that he shouldn't even have a visa,'' Mahoney told
The Associated Press.
   Bodin and Ms. Teague were about to leave for Moscow when they
were told their visas had been revoked, Mahoney said.
   ``This casts grave doubts on the sincerity of (Soviet leader
Mikhail) Gorbachev's policy of glasnost,'' said the stations'
president, Gene Pell, in Washington. ``Glasnost evidently does not
permit representatives of the largest Western broadcaster to
Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union to provide a firsthand account
of the summit to millions of listeners.''
   The two stations broadcast in 23 languages to Eastern Europe and
the Soviet Union.
   Malcolm E. Forbes Jr., chairman of the Board of International
Broadcasting, called on Gorbachev to reverse the decision. The
Washington-based board oversees the radio stations.
   President Reagan is scheduled to arrive in Moscow Sunday for his
fourth summit with Gorbachev since 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
