<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 0455EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonIndictments     05-28 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Indictments,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fourteen Pontiac Correctional Center Employees Indicted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM STRACENER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen state prison employees,
including a cellhouse superintendent and several guards, have been
indicted on charges of possessing and distributing marijuana and
cocaine, officials said.
   The indictment followed a two-month probe by the Illinois State
Police that brought charges against the superintendent, two
captains, three lieutenants and eight other employees, U.S.
Attorney J. William Roberts said Friday.
   Thirteen suspects were arrested Friday morning during a shift
change at Pontiac Correctional Center.
   Their cars and the guards' quarters outside the maximum-security
prison were searched but no drugs were found, said state
Corrections Director Michael Lane. They were released later on
personal recognizance bonds after appearing before a U.S.
magistrate.
   The other suspect, whose name was withheld, was still at large,
Roberts said.
   Prisoners apparently were not involved in the alleged conspiracy
and did not receive drugs, Roberts said.
   Lane said he didn't view the indictments as a black eye on his
agency, but rather as evidence the department is willing to clean
house when necessary.
   ``The number of arrests and prosecutions throughout the
Department of Corrections have increased every year for the past
five years,'' he said.
   ``These are not charges of distributing drugs within the prison.
They are charges of distributing drugs within the community, among
the guard ranks, among each other as well as some instances of
simple possession,'' Roberts said.
   The sealed indictments, returned Thursday by a federal grand
jury here, mark the biggest drug case in the state prison system in
recent years, Lane said.
   The suspects face charges of drug conspiracy, possession and
distribution involving cocaine and marijuana. If convicted, some
could face sentences up to 40 years in prison and a $2 million fine.
   More charges and arrests were expected as the probe continued,
Roberts said.
   The investigation, code-named ``Operation White Shirt,'' was
ordered by Lane, who described it as part of an effort to weed out
illegal drugs from the prison system.
   ``Regrettably, this is apparently what it's going to take to
have a drug-free workplace in the Department of Corrections,'' Lane
said.
   A former corrections officer, Lt. Cesar Roland Chavez, 34, of
Odell, was arrested March 17 in Bloomington on a charge of selling
cocaine. Authorities discovered Chavez kept a ledger said to
contain the names of people who bought drugs from him and those
with whom he conducted legitimate business.
   ``Chavez was a central figure,'' Roberts said.
   Chavez wasn't indicted by the grand jury and Roberts said he
doubts any federal charges will be filed against him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
