<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 0507EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Children-DrugMoney     05-28 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Children-Drug Money,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say There Is Little They Can Do About Money Hand Outs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug dealers are tossing money out of
their fancy cars in an effort to lure youngsters in a poor
neighborhood into the world of drug trafficking, police say, adding
there's little they can do to stop them.
   ``What do you charge them with? Littering? They are. They're
throwing bits of paper out the car window. The problem is everyone
is out there picking it up,'' Assistant City Attorney Peter Warner
said Friday.
   The money handouts probably will not last long, said Lt. Richard
Dugan, head of the narcotics unit. ``Their motive is just to make
themselves look good. Other people look at them and say, `Hey, wow,
look at how rich they are.'
   ``These people aren't enormously rich,'' Dugan said. ``They're
drug dealers, but they're not millionaires. They're driving flashy
cars and that's it. The rest of their life is nothing.''
   Monday through Wednesday, several people police say are believed
to be involved in drug dealing began throwing money _ mostly dollar
bills _ from the sun roofs of a blue Mercedes, a black Mercedes and
a BMW. There were some reports of bills as large as $50 winding up
in the grateful hands of neighborhood youngsters.
   ``If you've been to a parade and you know when the clowns come
by and throw candy and the kids all scurry _ it's the same thing,''
Warner said.
   Even though police know who the people are, they can't charge
them with a crime because no laws have been violated. While it's
not against the law to toss money into the street, officials have
considered citing the suspected dealers for littering or charging
them with creating a public nuisance.
   City Council member Bill Wilson said he received reports of
children ages 10 to 15 flocking after cars and picking up money.
   ``Five dollars, $10, even $20, just tossed out the window,''
Wilson said. ``They even set up contests among the kids and bet on
who will win. I heard that the winners get hundreds of dollars.''
   Police said the amount of money being tossed to children has
been exaggerated. Dugan said he understands the concerns of parents
in the neighborhood, but he cautioned against overreacting.
   ``I think the whole thing is blown out of proportion,'' he said.
``I think it's just a couple of isolated incidents. It doesn't have
any significance as far as I'm concerned.''
   But members of the Summit-University neighborhood say they're
outraged by the handouts.
   ``I am shocked,'' said the Rev. James W. Battle, pastor of Mount
Olivet Baptist Church. ``It's a new one on me. It doesn't make
sense to me. They already have more people selling drugs than they
need.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
