<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 0519EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     05-28 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Scriptwriters OK Waiver Contracts With 73 Independent
Producers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 12 weeks on the picket line, striking
TV and movie scriptwriters for such popular programs as ``The Cosby
Show'' and ``Highway to Heaven'' will return to work under
independent contracts.
   Seventy-three independent production companies had signed the
pacts by Friday, Writers Guild of America officials said. According
to union estimates, the signings will put 200 to 400 writers back
to work.
   WGA members overwhelmingly approved the contracts during voting
in New York and Los Angeles on Thursday, union spokeswoman Cheryl
Rhoden reported.
   Eighty-six percent of the 2,016 guild members who voted endorsed
the proposal, she said.
   Negotiators for both writers and the Alliance of Motion Picture
and Television Producers agreed to continue their negotiations to
completely resolve the strike. The two sides were to meet in small
groups today and had scheduled a formal bargaining session with a
federal mediator for Tuesday.
   In the meantime, the producers' group downplayed the signings of
the independent production companies as an insignificant episode in
the 3-month-old strike that has stalled preparations for the new
fall television season.
   Alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg estimated the independent
contracts, which give in to writers' key pay demands, cover about 1
percent of the union's working members, and none of the big
production companies that make up the backbone of the industry
group.
   ``Not one alliance member is in this group,'' Steinberg said of
the producers who had signed.
   Actor Michael Landon expressed gratification, however, that
Michael Landon Productions, the company that produces his show,
``Highway To Heaven,'' was able to come to terms with the writers.
   ``The only thing that matters to me is that it ends the strike
for the people that work for my company,'' Landon said. ``They have
all been innocent victims and now they can all get back to work.''
   Producers of other popular shows that signed agreements included
``The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson,'' ``It's Garry
Shandling's Show,'' and ``ALF.''
   However, Steinberg said many of those who had settled by Friday
were one-person writer-producer companies, including some that
produce TV shows that have been canceled, including the Smothers
Brothers' new comedy show and ``Days and Nights of Molly Dodd.''
   But Ms. Rhoden saw the defections as a break in management ranks
and called it a symbolic victory for striking writers.
   The three-year waiver contracts grant the striking writers' key
demand _ retention of the present formula for the residual payments
that writers get for syndication of one-hour television shows.
   Producers are seeking to tie the amount paid to writers to the
level of success or failure a show encounters in the syndication
market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
