<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-28 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Front Brings Rain, Stiff Winds to Pacific Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell along the northern Pacific coast today, ahead of a
strong cold front that brought cold, wet and windy weather to the
Pacific Northwest as thunderstorms rumbled through the Midwest.
   A winter storm watch was posted for this afternoon and tonight
in the Shasta Mountains of northern California as snow levels were
forecast to drop to near 3,000 feet by tonight. A winter storm
watch also was issued for late this afternoon and tonight in the
northern Sierra Nevada.
   A high wind watch was in effect today for western Nevada, where
damaging winds were possible near the eastern slopes of the
northern Sierra Nevada.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms extended from North Dakota
into Nebraska. Small hail and thunderstorm winds whipped up to 75
mph west of Scottsbluff, Neb.
   A band of showers and thunderstorms reached from south-central
Kansas across the Texas panhandle into southeastern New Mexico and
far western Texas. A few thunderstorms also dotted northwestern New
Mexico and southwest Colorado.
   In Kansas, a tornado touched down early Friday evening in
northwest Kearny County, while hail the size of golfballs pelted
areas near Fowler and near Scott City.
   Small tornadoes blew through south Florida Friday afternoon,
uprooting trees and causing minor property damage, officials said.
A girl who was injured after being tossed by a tornado was in good
condition, officials said.
   Today's forecast called for rain across Washington, Oregon,
northern Idaho and northern California; snow in the higher mountain
areas of northern California; showers and thunderstorms in northern
New England and south Florida; widely scattered thunderstorms,
mostly in the afternoon and early evening, from Montana to western
Texas, and from North Dakota to northwest Wisconsin; strong and
gusty winds over the Great Basin.
   Temperatures were forecast in the 80s or low 90s around much of
the nation; in the 60s and 70s in the Pacific coastal region and
the northern Rockies; in the 70s near the northern Great Lakes and
across Maine; in the 90s to around 100 across the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 38
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 84 degrees at
Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 63 fair; Boston 61 fair; Buffalo 58 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 58 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 52 fair;
Cleveland 59 fair; Detroit 60 fair; Miami 73 cloudy; New York 63
partly cloudy; Philadelphia 57 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 56 fair;
Portland, Maine 51 fair; Washington 60 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 63 thunderstorms; Chicago 67 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 69 fair; Denver 61 partly cloudy; Des Moines 67
fair; Indianapolis 58 fair; Kansas City 69 cloudy; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 68 fair; Nashville 58 fair; New Orleans 69 fair; St. Louis 66
fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 65 partly cloudy; Anchorage 55 cloudy; Las
Vegas 76 fair; Los Angeles 61 fair; Phoenix 86 fair; Salt Lake City
61 fair; San Diego 63 cloudy; San Francisco 59 drizzle; Seattle 53
showers.
   _Canada: Montreal 61 fair; Toronto 61 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
