<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 0527EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeacherAttack     05-28 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teacher Attack,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reading, Writing And Risk: A Bloody Week For NYC Teachers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite attacks on four New York City teachers
in a week, the number of teachers assaulted in the past three years
has decreased, mainly because of an increase in security guards in
elementary schools, officials say.
   The head of the teachers union on Friday acknowledged a downward
trend in attacks but said adding security personnel wasn't enough,
especially in light of the blood spilled during the week.
   ``One attack against a teacher is outrageous and to have four in
one week is just intolerable,'' said United Federation of Teachers
President Sandra Feldman. ``And we're afraid that this is just the
tip of the iceberg.''
   The UFT wants security guards in every school and police
officers deployed in troubled neighborhoods to protect teachers and
children involved in outdoor, after-school activities.
   The union is also pushing for legislation to make any physical
attack on a teacher a felony offense, even if it only involves
pushing or punching, Ms. Feldman said. A bill is pending in the
state Senate.
   She praised new schools Chancellor Richard Green for his
proposal to put metal detectors in five violence-prone schools this
fall.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch announced a ``summit meeting'' for Tuesday
to find out what can be done to improve teacher safety. It will be
attended by the chancellor, union leaders, the five district
attorneys and police commissioner.
   A 17-year-old Bronx youth was arrested Friday night and charged
in the latest attack, in which a physical education teacher was
beaten unconscious with a baseball bat after he confronted an
intruder rifling through students' gym bags outside a Bronx school
Thursday afternoon.
   Gary Smith, 37, was in critical but stable condition at Lincoln
Hospital late Friday after undergoing surgery for a ruptured right
eye. ``At this point we don't know if he'll see or not from that
eye,'' said Robert Medina, a hospital administrator.
   Smith, the fourth city school teacher assaulted during the week,
regained consciousness Friday morning, Medina said. The results of
a CAT scan were not immediately known.
   Teacher Douglas De Marco, who was knifed more than a dozen times
Monday by a mugger in the bathroom of a South Bronx grammar school,
said, ``there's something seriously wrong here.''
   The need for increased security has long been evident to De
Marco, who said he teaches in ``a neighborhood that's known for two
things: heroin and crack.''
   The other attacks included a teacher who was beaten up by a
student, the student's brother and sister; and a 71-year-old
teacher who was injured when she picked up an M-80 firecracker
tossed into her classroom.
   Yet the Board of Education said the number of assaults in city
schools have decreased, mainly because of an increase in security
guards in elementary schools.
   There were 1,322 assaults in the city's 1,000 schools in
1985-86, 1,335 in 1986-87, and 969 so far this year, board
spokesman Bob Terte said.
   Those figures included 337 teachers assaulted in 1985-86, 297 in
1986-87 and 198 this year, he said. The rest were on students and
other school personnel including custodians and cafeteria workers.
   Terte described an assault as anything from a shove against a
wall to more violent incidents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
