<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-HumanRights     05-28 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Human Rights,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pravda Accuses U.S. of Jailing Political Opponents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party daily Pravda has accused the
United States of ignoring its own human rights violations,
contending that 11,000 Americans are jailed in their own land for
political reasons.
   In a brief commentary two days before the scheduled arrival of
President Reagan for his fourth summit with Mikhail S. Gorbachev,
Pravda's Friday editions repeated the Kremlin's longstanding
accusations against the U.S. government.
   Pravda said American political groups and lawyers contend 11,000
people are imprisoned in the United States for political actions in
defense of blacks, American Indians, independence for Puerto Rico
and other causes.
   It lists among those people the Soviets consider political
prisoners Leonard Peltier, an American Indian sentenced for killing
two FBI agents.
   Pravda also said there were 200 Americans jailed for anti-war
activities and that hundreds were arrested in recent demonstrations
in Nevada against nuclear weapons testing.
   Repeating the Soviet government's standard accusations about
U.S. human rights violations, Pravda said millions of people in the
United States are homeless and unemployed. The
   Soviets contend basic human rights include provision of jobs and
housing for everyone.
   The commentary suggested the United States pay attention to its
own problems in guaranteeing human rights before criticizing the
shortcomings in other nations.
</TEXT>
