<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Beauty     05-28 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Beauty,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Organizer Says Beauty Contest To Go On In Scaled-Down Form</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sponsor of Beijing's first beauty contest said
today that the event would take place after all, although it will
be scaled down and not be televised.
   Earlier this week, Beijing Television Studio, one of two
sponsors of the capital's first beauty contest since the Communist
takeover in 1949, said the pageant had been canceled because
``conditions for such an event are not yet ripe.''
   But Contemporary Television magazine said today that the finals
would be held as planned on June 5.
   ``We have planned this event out very well. It is not like
beauty contests in other places in China. We are not following the
`beauty contest fever,''' said a spokeswoman who identified herself
only as Guan.
   After the announcement in April that Beijing would host a
contest to select ten ``Girls of Youth and Elegance,'' other cities
quickly followed suit, creating a beauty contest craze in China and
generating much discussion about whether they are appropriate in a
country with a low standard of living.
   Organizers of a beauty contest in Jiangxi province, one of the
nation's poorest, were criticized for hosting the 15-day event when
1 million of the province's farmers were still living in poverty.
   Shanghai called off its contest for a ``Shanghai Maiden'' two
weeks ago, also giving the reason that ``conditions are not ripe.''
   In Canton, organizers said they would go ahead with its beauty
contest, and the final selection for ``Miss Canton'' and ``Mr.
Canton'' were scheduled for today. But the local media was told to
play down the event and the organizing television station also
scrapped plans to televise the contest live.
   Organizers of the Beijing contest planned to choose their ten
beauties through a television contest after 40 days of preliminary
judging.
   However, Guan said the finals would not be televised, reporters
would not be allowed to attend and there would be no news
conference afterwards.
   She did not say if only foreign reporters were to be barred.
   When China held its first beauty contest in 1985 in Canton, only
Chinese reporters were allowed to attend because organizers
apparently were afraid of negative publicity.
   More than 800 Beijing women signed up for the competition, and
the field had been narrowed down to 50 by last week.
   Contestants are judged on their talent in singing, dancing,
reading and answering questions designed to reveal their knowledge
and moral values.
</TEXT>
