<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SmallKidnapping     05-28 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Small Kidnapping,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Sentences Man To Death in Kidnap-Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Daniel J. Edwards sentenced himself to die
when he kidnapped a prominent businessman, buried him alive in a
homemade wooden box and left him to suffocate, prosecutors said.
   After six days of testimony, jurors on Monday convicted Edwards,
31, in the murder and kidnapping of Stephen Small. The panel
deliberated less than one hour Friday before sentencing him to die.
   ``When they rolled that box into the courtroom on Day One, I
would say his fate was decided,'' said defense attorney Thomas
Allen. ``You're always disappointed when the jury doesn't buy your
arguments, but it was no surprise.''
   Nancy D. Rish, 26, who lived with Edwards in Bourbonnais, also
was charged with murder and kidnapping. She awaits trial.
   In closing arguments on the death penalty, prosecutor Frank
Nowicki of the attorney general's staff called Edwards a diabolical
criminal whose cruelty demanded the death penalty.
   He challenged jurors to imagine ``a worse way to die,'' as he
stood in front of the box in which Small's body was found Sept. 4,
1987, two days after he was kidnapped.
   ``Imagine Stephen Small when that lid closed ... his life coming
to an end,'' Nowicki said. ``Imagine the panic he felt, the
helplessness ... to claw, to scrape, to scratch.''
   Edwards ``sentenced himself to death'' by his own actions,
Nowicki said.
   But Allen said there was ``some character'' in Edwards and asked
the jury to spare his life.
   Small, 40, member of a prominent media family and great-grandson
of the late Illinois Gov. Len Small, was lured from his home and
abducted, and a $1 million ransom was demanded in telephone calls
to his wife, Nancy.
   But she was unable to understand her husband's tape-recorded
instructions for delivery of the cash. Police found Small's body in
a wooded area between Kankakee and the Indiana border.
   During the trial, jurors saw the coffin-sized plywood box where
Small suffocated and listened to chilling tape-recordings of Small
saying his kidnapper had put him in a ``grave'' where he would die
unless the $1 million ransom was paid quickly.
   Defense attorney Sheldon Reagan maintained that it was a
``tragic accident,'' in which Small was buried with candy bars,
lights and water but a faulty air-supply system. He also suggested
that someone other than Edwards kidnapped Small.
</TEXT>
