<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 0604EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Summit-FishingAgreement     05-28 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Fishing Agreement,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit-Reagan Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan, Gorbachev Expected To Sign Fisheries Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American fishermen would be allowed to fish in
Soviet waters for the first time under an agreement that Soviet
Leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and President Reagan are expected to
sign during their summit meeting.
   The agreement also would require joint efforts to conserve and
manage Bering Sea fisheries.
   ``We reached agreement in principle two days ago in Moscow,'' Ed
Wolfe, the State Department's ambassador for oceans and fisheries,
said Friday. ``It will be signed during the summit.''
   Wolfe declined to say when the signing was scheduled during the
Moscow summit, which begins Sunday. He spoke by telephone from his
Washington, D.C., office and said he had just returned Thursday
night from Moscow.
   The 10-page pact is a final version of a tentative agreement
reached by the two countries in February.
   ``This is exceedingly important to us economically,'' said Arni
Thomson, executive secretary of the Alaska Crab Coalition in
Seattle.
   Industry and congressional sources said that under the agreement:
   _ U.S. fishermen will, for the first time, have access to crab,
bottomfish and other resources in Soviet waters adjacent to Alaska.
Thomson said his group was negotiating for licenses and space in
Siberian ports.
   ``We would like to be the first to fish in their zone,'' he said
of the 175 U.S. crab boats that have had pinched seasons for nearly
a decade.
   Most deals, he said, would involve joint ventures with the
Soviets in fishing and marketing. The Soviets would gain access to
superior American crabbing techniques and profit from trade at the
ports.
   _ The Soviets, who for years have been allowed to fish U.S.
waters, will have greater access to under-utilized American
fisheries, including mackerel off the U.S. East Coast and hake off
the West Coast.
   _ The United States and the Soviet Union identify as areas of
mutual interest management of fisheries resources in the Bering
Sea, including international waters.
   ``The agreement specifically commits the two nations to consult
and work together on ways to address the effects of unregulated
fishing in the `doughnut hole,''' Rep. Don Bonker, D-Wash., said
Friday.
   The doughnut hole is a triangular-shaped, 50,000-square-mile
chunk of international waters where U.S. officials fear heavy
fishing by several countries could result in the decline of
bottomfish stocks. Another area of mutual interest for the United
States and Soviet Union is management of salmon stocks on the high
seas.
   The agreement is a further example of the improving relations
between the United States and the Soviet Union, said Wolfe.
   The United States and the Soviet Union for the past decade have
conducted joint fishing efforts, with American catcher boats
providing Soviet processing ships with hake, yellowfin sole and
other bottomfish.
   Thomson said the latest agreement could mean millions of dollars
to crabbers, who have had lean years the past decade after Alaska's
king crab fishery inexplicably shriveled up.
   However, he said fishermen, whose boats require a $5,000
investment a day to break even while fishing, are concerned about
costs the Soviets might impose.
   If a fleet of 15 to 20 of the crab boats were to fish for the
Soviets, he said, the boats would need a return of $15 million to
$20 million for six months' work.
   He said Soviets were especially interested in deepwater crab
fishing, a technique American fishermen have learned only the past
five or six years. It is the only way crab in deep water can be
harvested, he said.
   Bonker said the agreement could mean greater cooperation in
collecting fisheries data in the Bering Sea for management and
monitoring the fishing boats from various countries. Both countries
have accused others, including Japan, of pirating their fisheries.
   ``We have a resource that is in U.S. waters, Soviet waters and
international waters,'' said Bonker of the fish that wander across
political boundaries. ``It moves around. We all have a stake in
whether that resource is overfished or depleted.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
