<HEAD>Scholarship Fund Established In Victim's Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scholarship fund has been established in the
name of a boy who was bludgeoned to death by a classmate with a
baseball bat, according to Northeastern University's College of
Criminal Justice.
   Shaun Ouillette, 14, was killed Nov. 20, 1986, by Rod Matthews,
15, a classmate at Canton High School. Matthews was convicted in
March of second-degree murder by a Norfolk County Superior Court
jury.
   The Shaun Ouillette Memorial Fund is designed to provide tuition
assistance to an incoming freshman interested in pursuing a career
in law enforcement. Jeanne Quinn, Ouillette's mother, said her son
had hoped to become a police officer.
   The scholarship's selection committee will pick a graduate of a
Massachusetts high school who is in financial need to receive the
award.
