<HEAD>Two British Men Wanted In U.S. Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two British citizens wanted in the United States on
charges of illegally exporting military-oriented high technology
materials from the United States to the Soviet bloc have been
arrested in Rome, police said today.
   One of the men is also under investigation for possible links
with Libya, according to Italy's anti-terrorist police.
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the pair
was arrested earlier in the week after arriving at Rome's Leonardo
da Vinci airport on flights from London.
   The two, identified as Brian Butcher, 55, of Southampton, and
Clifford Chadwick, 52, of Rochdale, were taken into custody on
international warrants issued by U.S. Customs Service officials in
Boston, Mass., and Phoenix, Ariz. the Italian police said.
   The suspects were being held in a Rome jail. A formal
extradition request from the United States was expected to arrive
shortly.
   Butcher and Chadwick are charged with fraud and illegal export
of high technology that can be used for civilian and military
purposes, the police officials said.
   The material was allegedly delivered to Romania, Bulgaria and
Poland.
   The officials said they could not divulge the exact type of
material involved, but the Italian news agency ANSA described it as
photocopies of electronic equipment for submarines, planes and
missiles.
   The officials said Chadwick is also under investigation in Italy
on suspicion of involvement in procurement of arms for Libya and
attacks against Libyan dissidents.
   Several opponents of Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi have
been assassinated in Italy in recent years.
