<2ND_LINE>PM-South Asia-Floods,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rains, Snow Pushing Rivers Over Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from flooding in
northeastern India rose to 26 today and officials in neighboring
Bangladesh said thousands of families were rendered homeless by
rivers that overflowed their banks.
   Heavy rain continued to hamper rescue workers in the northeast
Indian state of Assam, where the Brahmaputra River and its
tributaries have been rising for six days, the Press Trust of India
reported.
   Thousands of acres of farmland have been inundated and thousands
of families have moved to make-shift camps on higher ground, the
news agency said.
   In Dhaka, the capital of Bangladesh, officials in the Water
Control Ministry said rivers were being swelled by the annual snow
melt from the Himalayan mountains and heavy, pre-monsoon rains.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said more
than 200,000 acres of land had been flooded. They said that if the
water did not recede soon, some of the country's rice crop would be
destroyed.
   More than 5,000 people were reported marooned in the tea-growing
district of Sylhet in northeastern Bangladesh.
   Rice is the staple food for Bangladesh's 105 million people. The
country last year was hard-hit by floods. Nearly one-quarter of its
population was dislocated at the height of rain problems last
summer.
</TEXT>
