<HEAD>Supreme Soviet Called Into Session to Ratify Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Soviet, the Kremlin's nominal
parliament, was called into special session today to ratify the
U.S.-Soviet treaty banning intermediate and shorter range nuclear
missiles.
   The session came a day after the U.S. Senate overwhelmingly
approved the document and appeared aimed at securing approval of
the treaty before the arrival Sunday of President Reagan.
   Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev are expected to
formally exchange final copies of the document in Moscow on
Wednesday.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze told his
colleagues on the lawmaking body at the start of the session that
the Soviet Union was not responding to pressure from the United
States and that the treaty would free both countries' resources for
peaceful uses.
   A Foreign Ministry briefing for reporters at the summit press
center was abruptly canceled and journalists were informed that the
Supreme Soviet was meeting.
   Friday the U.S. Senate voted 93-5 to approve the first arms
treaty between the superpowers in 16 years.
   Earlier today, the head of the Soviet Peace Committee welcomed
the U.S. Senate's approval and predicted Soviet ratification would
follow shortly.
</TEXT>
