<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Giuffre-Admissions     05-28 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Giuffre-Admissions,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Lifts Ban on Admissions at Giuffre</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The emergency room at the James C. Giuffre
Medical Center has been allowed to reopen as state health officials
relax restrictions on the hospital where admissions were banned 15
days ago.
   But the Pennsylvania Department of Health continues to restrict
the number of medical and surgical patients at the hospital to 80.
The hospital has the capacity for 148 such patients.
   The emergency room was reopened ``because our staff is pleased
with the continuing progress made at the facility over the past
week,'' Bruce Reimer, a health department spokesman, said Friday.
   The state banned most new admissions to Giuffre on May 12 and
ordered it to shut down its emergency room and surgical operations
after inspectors found serious lapses in the quality of care. The
department found 124 deficiencies, including 12 questionable deaths
after surgery and 29 cases of unnecessary surgery.
   The state held the hospital's board of directors and chief
executive officer Dr. James C. Giuffre responsible and ordered
personnel changes.
   On Wednesday the hospital named a new 15-member board of
directors, ousting Giuffre and naming Philadelphia businessman G.
Fred DiBona as board chairman.
   The emergency room reopened at 1 p.m. Friday, immediately after
the hospital was notified that the state ban had been lifted, said
William L. Vazquez, the hospital's president.
   The move Friday effectively removes the ban on admissions, which
had been partially lifted last week when the state allowed surgery
to resume.
   The hospital's drug and alcohol rehabilitation unit and its
outpatient primary-care clinic were unaffected by the state
restrictions.
</TEXT>
