<HEAD>Jewish Refuseniks Plan Demonstrations During Summit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Jewish refuseniks is planning a series
of protests during the Moscow summit to draw attention to the
plight of Soviet Jews denied permission to emigrate.
   ``The refusals have pounded down like hail'' since President
Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev met last December in
Washington, said activist Marina Durnovo.
   Reagan arrives here Sunday for the five-day summit.
   The group plans three demonstrations, at 6 p.m. local time at
the Lenin library in downtown Moscow.
   Many well-known Jewish activists have been allowed to emigrate
from the Soviet Union under Gorbachev, leaving behind many others
who have been denied permission to leave.
   Activist Yuri Semenovsky, said he had conducted a survey of some
of the estimated 2 million Jews in the Soviet Union, and concluded
that 30 percent of them would like to leave. His study appeared in
the March issue of ``Referendum'', an independent journal published
by the ``Press Club Glasnost,'' a dissident organization that tests
the limits of Gorbachev's reforms.
   Semenovsky said that 200,000 Jews had already applied to leave
the country, and that many, like himself, had been harassed by the
authorities and forced out of their jobs, and that many others were
afraid to ask.
   The number of Jews receiving emigration visas rose to 1,400 this
winter and jumped to 1,800 in April, said Yevgeny Rubinstain,
another member of the group.
</TEXT>
