<HEAD>Soldiers Fight Arabs Attacking Army Base</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with clashes today, edits to trim.
No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers today fired tear gas and
rubber bullets at Palestinian protesters who threw stones and
bottles at a refugee camp's army headquarters in the occupied Gaza
Strip.
   Gaza City was paralyzed by a general strike, and groups of
Palestinian youths threw stones at cars and set tires ablaze.
   In the occupied West Bank, activists of the Israeli left-wing
Peace Now movement drove in two convoys towards the area's largest
city of Nablus. The movement planned to stage a symbolic withdrawal
from the area.
   Since anti-occupation unrest broke out Dec. 8, Israeli soldiers
have killed 198 Palestinians. Two Israelis also have died.
   In the Jabaliya refugee camp in the Gaza Strip, a firebomb was
thrown at an army patrol, an Arab reporter said. He said soldiers
entered and searched homes, confiscating identity cards of about 25
residents.
   Several Palestinians were ordered to park their vehicles in
front of the military administration building in the camp to
prevent stone-throwing attacks, he said.
   Later, youths attacked army headquarters in the camp with stones
and bottles, and troops responded by firing rubber bullets and tear
gas grenades. There were no reports of injuries.
   The protests came in an apparent response to the calls made by
underground leaders of the Arab uprising in the occupied lands, who
have called on their followers to challenge the troops and raise
outlawed Palestinian flags.
   This week, Israel's Supreme Court upheld the army order barring
Peace Now from displaying signs, distributing leaflets, meeting
with the Arabs or passing through West Bank towns.
   In protest, Peace Now held a demonstration on the outskirts of
Jerusalem, removing signs from the cars, Israel radio said.
   The radio also reported that the army on Friday uprooted several
rows of trees in the West Bank village of Shuweika, claiming these
served as a shelter for firebombers.
   Earlier this week, an Arab woman and her son were burned to
death near Shuweika after their car was hit by a firebomb. Soldiers
were patrolling in the area at the time, and the firebomb had
apparently been intended for an Israeli vehicle.
   On Friday, a 3-year-old Palestinian girl and two teen-agers died
after being caught up in clashes with Israeli soldiers.
   A leading Palestinian journalist was released from jail Friday
and called on Israel to ease its crackdown in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip and launch peace negotiations through an
international conference.
   Rajwan Abu Eish, head of the Arab Journalists Association in the
occupied lands, had been jailed without trial six months ago.
   Also Friday, hundreds of Arabs waving Palestinian flags and
black flags of mourning marched to the house of Ahmad Wazir, the
cousin of the assassinated PLO military chief, Khalil Wazir, an
Arab reporter said.
   Wazir, better known as Abu Jihad, was gunned down last month
outside Tunis, Tunisia, reportedly by Israeli commandos.
</TEXT>
