<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Summit-SovietINF 3rdLd-Writethru a0512 05-28 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Soviet INF, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0512,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Follow U.S. Senate in Ratifying Medium-Range Missile
Treaty</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new penultimate graf, bgng, Foreign Ministr xxx etc.,
to UPDATE with Gerasimov quote.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   live on Soviet television.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The collective Soviet presidency today unanimously
ratified the superpower treaty scrapping both nations' medium-range
nuclear missiles, swiftly following the U.S. Senate's approval a
day earlier.
   Approval by both nations of the accord signed at the Washington
summit in December clears away any doubt about the treaty's fate
and strikes a positive note on the eve of President Reagan's
arrival for his summit with Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorachev in
Moscow.
   The session of the presidium was shown live on Soviet television
_ something that rarely has been done in the past.
   ``The present summit opens up new vistas,'' said Lev N. Zaikov,
a Politburo member and Moscow Communist Party boss, adding that the
meeting ``inspires us with hope that even greater agreements will
be reached.''
   A session of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, a 36-member
body headed by President Andrei A. Gromyko, met in special session
and cast a traditional unanimous vote in favor of the pact.
   The U.S. Senate voted 93-5 on Friday to approve the accord, and
a Soviet official predicted early Saturday that ratification by the
Kremlin would follow shortly.
   The Presidium session began less than 16 hours after the Senate
action.
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze hailed the treaty as the
product of the Kremlin's policy of ``New Thinking'' on
international matters. Shevardnadze said the funds saved on weapons
production would add 300 million rubles ($508 million dollars) for
non-military uses like environmental protection and social services.
   The foreign minister said the treaty was not the result of
pressure on the Soviet Union applied by the United States, but a
mutually beneficial pact that would advance stability.
   Politburo member Yegor K. Ligachev said the treaty could herald
the start of restructuring U.S.-Soviet relations, but ``there are
forces in the United States and Europe opposed to disarmament.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said the
ratification by both sides ``was a very good prelude to the summit
here in Moscow.''
   Reagan and Gorbachev plan to exchange the final texts of the
treaty as ratified by each side at a ceremony Wednesday after their
talks on arms control, human rights, regional issues and superpower
relations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
