<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Cyprus 2ndLd-Writethru   05-28 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyprus, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0482,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkish Soldier Crosses Green Line, Killed By Police After Slaying
Guardsman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with report that Turkish soldier
was killed by Greek police who stormed house, PICKS UP graf 6 `The
dead...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police killed a Turkish soldier today
after he tried to rape a Greek Cypriot woman, shot to death a
national guardsman and wounded another, Greek Cypriot officials
said.
   Government-run radio said police stormed the woman's house in
the village of Athienou southeast of Nicosia several hours after
the guardsmen were shot. They then fatally shot the soldier after
he tried to open fire on police, said the broadcast, quoting
government officials.
   The house lies near the volatile Green Line that separates the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot populations on this Mediterranean island.
It was the second fatal clash near the Green Line in a week.
   U.N. spokesman Charles Gaulkin said investigations of today's
violence were under way.
   Greek Cypriot police said the woman escaped unharmed after the
break-in around dawn. They said the Turkish soldier was dead at the
scene.
   The National Guard said the intruder was a Turkish soldier who
tried to rape the woman. About 30,000 Turkish soldiers are
stationed on the island.
   The dead guardsman was identified as Charalambos Charalambous,
about 18 or 19 years old. The injured guardsman, Ioannis Kaleshis,
was taken to Larnaca General Hospital and listed in serious
condition.
   On May 21, U.N. troops from the Austrian contingent here shot to
death a Turkish Cypriot, Hussein Kafa. The United Nations said Kafa
had wounded an Austrian peacekeeper near the mixed Greek-Turkish
village of Pyla.
   Later that day, a second Austrian peacekeeper was wounded by two
of Kafa's relatives while he guarded an Austrian post, authorities
said. The two relatives were later taken into custody in connection
with the incident.
   Pyla is the only village where Turkish Cypriots and Greek
Cypriots still live together despite the 14-year-old partition of
the island.
   After the incident, Maj. Gen. Gunther Greindl, the Austrian
commander of U.N. peacekeepers in Cyprus, dismissed Turkish Cypriot
complaints against him.
   ``I consider the charges made against the United Nations Force
in Cyprus generally, and me personally, are totally unjustified,''
he said in a statement.
   Rauf Dentash, president of the northern Turkish Cypriot
breakaway state, had charged that Greindl ordered Austrian troops
to harass Kafa and held the U.N. commander responsible for the
fatal shooting.
   Turkish Cypriots planned a rally in Pyla on Sunday to protest
Kafa's killing.
   Troops from Turkey invaded the northern section of this
Mediterranean island in 1974 after Greek Cypriot activists staged a
coup, seeking to unite the island with Greece.
   Turkish Cypriots make up about 18 percent of the island's
population of 650,000 people. Denktash's government is recognized
only by Turkey.
</TEXT>
