<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF-FirefighterDeaths     05-28 0131</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-Firefighter Deaths,0133</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On-duty Firefighter Deaths Up in 1987.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUINCY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heart attacks were the No. 1 killer of
firefighters who died in the line of duty last year, striking down
56 of 124 fatally injured firefighters, according to the National
Fire Protection Association.
   The number of firefighters who died in the line of duty in 1987
was up 9.7 percent over the previous year and the highest since 134
died in 1981, the group reported Friday.
   There were 72 volunteers and 52 career firefighters among the
1987 fatalities, according to the annual report of the non-profit
group that claims more than 44,000 members nationwide.
   In addition to heart attacks, the major categories of fatal
injury were internal trauma, 28 deaths; asphyxiation, 13 deaths;
and crushing, 12 deaths.
</TEXT>
