<DOCNO> AP880528-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 1054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-ThatcherMorality Bjt   05-28 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thatcher Morality, Bjt,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bible-Quoting Thatcher Stirs Furious Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher confided to a
guest recently that piled on her bedside table are collections of
religious and philosophical essays.
   The repercussions have been enormous. There are major speeches
aligning her rigorous policies of free enterprise and self-reliance
with Christian tenets. Biblical allusions are traded in Parliament,
and there is furious public debate about whether God is on the side
of Thatcherism.
   Aides say the Thatcher crusade to stake out the moral high
ground for her right-wing policies partly reflects anger and
resentment at the most persistent criticism of her nine-year
tenure: that she is uncaring, favors the well-off, and has divided
Britain.
   Mrs. Thatcher, an Anglican who grew up under the strict
Methodism of her father, a small-town grocer, has launched the
moral offensive along with a radical third term program described
as ``verging on the wicked'' by David Jenkins, the bishop of Durham
in northern England.
   It includes a welfare shake-up, big tax breaks for the
better-off and plans for an unpopular local tax.
   Gerald Priestland, a leading author on religious affairs, sees
Mrs. Thatcher's public espousal of ``basic corner shop Wesleyan
Methodism'' as seeking a deeper foundation for her political
philosophy.
   Priestland, 60, a former religious affairs correspondent for the
British Broadcasting Corp., said Mrs. Thatcher button-holed him
last month at a party at her 10 Downing St. residence.
   ``She confided that she has at her bedside the latest collection
of essays by the chief rabbi, by (English Roman Catholic leader)
Cardinal Basil Hume and by the English theological writer C.S.
Lewis,'' Priestland said in a telephone interview.
   ``She is now taking an intense interest in that sort of thing. I
think it is partly because as we get older, we do, don't we?
   ``But she also sees her premiership as more than a pair of dates
and hoping it will be regarded as something of a movement.
   ``She is not ashamed of Thatcherism and is probably trying to
dig its foundation a bit deeper.''
   Politicians in Britain _ a nominally Protestant country where
only about 10 percent of the 56 million people attend church
regularly _ rarely make references to religion. Being an
acknowledged agnostic is no handicap to election.
   Mrs. Thatcher, however, has dotted recent speeches with passages
on family life, morality and personal responsibility.
   In a major address to the assembly of the Church of Scotland
this month, she declared that the message of the Old and New
Testaments is that ``we must work and use our talents to create
wealth.''
   ``It is not the creation of wealth that is wrong, but the love
of money for its own sake,'' said the 62-year-old Conservative
Party leader.
   ``We simply cannot delegate the exercise of mercy and generosity
to others.''
   Quoting from her recent reading, she added, ``Christianity is
about spiritual redemption, not social reform.''
   In testy exchanges in the House of Commons, opposition Labor
Party leader Neil Kinnock taunted: ``Which passage of the Bible
inspired all that? Could it have been Matthew 27:24, when Pilate
took water and washed his hands?''
   She retorted: ``You debase everything.''
   The archbishop of Canterbury, the Most Rev. Robert Runcie, gave
a guarded endorsement to the Thatcher forays into religious
philosophy, saying he agreed with her advocacy of wealth creation.
   ``But I would want to ask a little more about the questions of
making wealth and at same time dividing a society in a way which
makes the people who have fallen behind, through no fault of their
own, feel on the edge of things,'' Runcie said in a radio interview.
   Methodist leaders were less charitable after Mrs. Thatcher, in
another speech Wednesday, likened her policies to the philosophy of
John Wesley, who founded Methodism 250 years ago. She quoted Wesley
as saying, ``Gain all you can ... give all you can.''
   ``Mrs. Thatcher is casting about for a reply to the criticisms
that have come from the churches,'' said Methodist Church secretary
general, the Rev. Brian Duckworth. ``Wesley's sermon was a ...
warning against greed.''
   Labor's Kinnock said Mrs. Thatcher's latest ``special brand of
born-again conservativism ... has nauseated people right across the
political and religious spectrum.''
   Social Democratic Party leader David Owen jibed: ``There's no
political party with a through line to God.''
</TEXT>
