<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Mecham,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Returns Home, Addresses Altamont Graduates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTAMONT, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evan Mecham, who was impeached and ousted
as governor of Arizona, returned to his roots and told Altamont
High School graduates to study the Constitution and understand the
freedoms that have made America great.
   In Friday's commencement address Mecham made no reference to the
problems that led to his impeachment.
   In his 20-minute address, Mecham spoke of the Founding Fathers,
religion and character, which he called ``that which governs you
when no one else is watching.''
   Mecham once was the junior class president at Altamont High,
where he graduated 46 years ago.
   ``Forty-six years go faster than you think, you'd better watch
how you spend it,'' he advised the 48 graduating students.
   After the speech on the school's football field, the graduates
in red-and-white gowns and roughly 600 spectators gave Mecham a
standing ovation.
   Mecham, 64, became the seventh U.S. governor to be removed from
office in an impeachment trial when he was convicted April 4 by the
Arizona Senate for obstructing justice and misusing state funds.
   The Senate did not debate a third charge, that Mecham concealed
a $350,000 campaign loan on his financial disclosure forms, but the
former governor and his brother Willard will go on trial next week
in Phoenix on fraud and perjury charges. The jury in that case was
sworn in Friday.
</TEXT>
