<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 1136EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh-Fire     05-28 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh-Fire,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>80 Injured in Fire at Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire raced through a refugee camp on
the outskirts of Dhaka on Saturday and injured at least 80 people
and left 17,000 homeless, police and fire officials said.
   A police officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
blaze wiped out most of the shanties in the camp at Mirpour, north
of the city. The fire was believed caused by an electrical
short-circuit.
   The camp housed Biharis awaiting resettlement in Pakistan. The
Biharis, who are Moslems, originated in India but settled in the
territory once known as East Pakistan. The territory became
Bangladesh in 1971, after a war with Pakistan.
   Thousands of Biharis have been resettled in Pakistan, but nearly
250,000 remain in Bangladesh awaiting transfer. The resettlement
program has been suspended for lack of funds.
   Nasim Khan, a leader of the Biharis, complained that there are
often fires at the refugee camps because of poor construction.
   ``Our repeated requests to the concerned authorities to do
something about it have produced no results,'' Khan said. He
estimated it would cost $3 million to rebuild the camp and replace
the families' lost goods.
   There was no word on the conditions of those injured.
</TEXT>
