<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Hostage     05-28 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Hostage,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freed French Hostage Describes Wine Vow Made To God</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former hostage Jean-Paul Kauffmann, a
French journalist and wine expert, has sworn off wine until August
to keep a vow he made while a captive of Shiite Moslem extremists
in Lebanon.
   But friends have a cellarful of Bordeaux awaiting the countdown
three months from the date of his May 4 release.
   Kauffmann, 44, editor-in-chief of the quarterly wine magazine
L'amateur de Bordeaux, vowed to God during his three-year captivity
that if he were freed he would not drink wine for three months,
according to an interview in the June issue of Wine Spectator.
   Kauffmann's magazine is a quarterly devoted to the wines of
Bordeaux, where some of the world's finest vintages are grown.
   During Kauffmann's captivity, Jean-Michel Cazes, owner of
Chateau Lynch Bages, put away 200 bottles of top Bordeaux in a
special cellar as a gesture of support by the region's vintners.
   ``We're extremely happy to have him back,'' said Cazes. ``I'm
ready to turn it over to him whenever he wants it.''
   Kauffmann was abducted while on assignment for a French news
weekly.
   ``One day when I reached bottom, I made a vow not to drink for
three months following my liberation,'' Kauffman said, explaining
that during his detention he read the Bible and became religious.
   He decided to sacrifice something important in hopes that his
prayers for freedom would be answered, the magazine said.
   Kauffman was held by the same Shiite Moslem extremists who are
believed to be holding most of the 18 foreign hostages _ including
nine Americans _ remaining in Lebanon. The longest-held is Terry A.
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press,
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Kauffmann said his teetotaling captors _ Islam forbids alcohol _
thought he was a drunkard because they saw a picture of him at a
wine tasting.
   ``It was a tasting at Chateau d'Yquem. I had 15 glasses in front
of me. In their eyes that couldn't be anything but a scene of utter
drunkenness,'' he said.
   Kauffmann said he tried to explain that the taster sips wine and
spits it out.
   ``I don't believe I was able to convince the Islamic Jihad of
the subtleties of wine tasting,'' he added.
</TEXT>
