<1ST_LINE>u i PM-JournalistFreed 5thLd-Writethru   05-28 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Journalist Freed, 5th Ld - Writethru,a0526,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede KABUL</HEAD>
<HEAD>Afghans Free Jailed French Photographer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout UPDATE with Guillo quotes, CORRECT length of
time since capture. Edits to trim. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan authorities today freed a French
photojournalist captured nine months ago and convicted of spying
after he entered Afghanistan with rebel fighters.
   Alain Guillo told a news conference in New Delhi after his
release: ``I would like to go back, if possible.''
   Asked if he would again go in with guerrillas, he said: ``That
doesn't really matter.''
   He was freed in Kabul, the Afghan capital, earlier in the day
after Gilbert Perol, secretary general of the French Foreign
Ministry, presented a letter from President Francois Mitterrand to
Afghan leader Najib.
   Guillo said he believed he was released because of the French
intervention and the summit beginning Sunday between President
Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   He said his imprisonment in Kabul was difficult.
   ``I wasn't treated too badly, but I was morally brutalized,'' he
said. ``For the first four months, I had no newspapers, books or
paper. I was always under surveillance and deprived of fundamental
rights.''
   Guillo, 45, arrived in New Delhi en route to Paris and reunion
with his family. He was to depart early Sunday on an Air France
flight.
   Guillo told the news conference at the home of French Ambassador
Andre Lewin that he had no advance warning of his release. Najib
announced his pardon Friday.
   He said he was captured Aug. 28 by Afghan security police after
he had entered Afghanistan from Pakistan with the rebels, who were
fighting Soviet and government troops.
   ``For 15 days, they hesitated between killing me on the spot and
arresting me formally,'' Guillo said of the Afghan police. ``They
would have blamed the killing on the Mujahedeen,'' he said,
referring to the rebels.
   Guillo was convicted Jan. 4 on charges of ``espionage and
subversive activities'' and sentenced to 10 years in prison.
   He has denied he was spying.
   A French official in Kabul who spoke on condition of anonymity
said no conditions were attached to the release and no money was
paid. ``There was no agreement, no special considerations,'' he
said.
   Guillo arrived aboard an Aryana Afghan Airlines flight from
Kabul wearing a white shirt, gray trousers and black windbreaker.
He was clean-shaven and appeared relaxed.
   Embassy officials said Guillo would rest for several hours at
the ambassador's residence before resuming his trip to Paris aboard
an Air France flight.
   In Paris, a spokesman for the French Foreign Ministry welcomed
Guillo's release.
   ``This liberation brings to a happy conclusion contacts taken
with Afghan authorities to obtain the pardon of the French
journalist,'' the spokesman said.
   There was no immediate word on the fate of another imprisoned
Western journalist, Fausto Biloslavo, an Italian who worked for the
small Albatross News Agency.
   Afghan Foreign Ministry spokesman Abdul Fatah Weidi said today
he had no information on when or if the Italian would be released.
Earlier, Western diplomatic sources said they expected Biloslavo's
release soon.
   Biloslavo was captured in July 1987 after entering Afghanistan
from Pakistan with the guerrillas and also convicted of spying.
Guillo shared a cell with him.
   Anti-communist guerrillas have been fighting the Soviet-backed
regime in Kabul since 1978. Soviet troops entered Afghanistan a
year later to prop up the Afghan government but began withdrawing
earlier this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
