<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-Rock     05-28 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Rock,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Heavy Metal' Blares For Sedate Pre-Summit Rock Concert</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boy George or no Boy George, the blaring beat of
``heavy metal'' reverberated through the night as thousands of
Soviet teen-agers, many dressed in jeans and punk-style outfits,
sat mesmerized at a pre-summit rock concert under the open skies of
Gorky Park.
   They clapped politely at the end of each song and waved small
paper flags printed with a big heart divided by the Stars and
Stripes and the hammer and sickle.
   ``Gorky Park, Central Park, what's the difference?'' said
William Sloane Coffin, a veteran American peace activist who said
he saw little difference between the concert and similar
ear-splitting events in the United States.
   Except that in America, if the music is any good, there is more
pandemonium. The Soviet crowd was sedate by comparison. They
clapped politely at the end of each song and waved their small
flags. At one point as a pop group began its set, people screamed
briefly but immediately sat down.
   Sasha, a 24-year-old Soviet, said young people didn't dare act
out for fear of reprisals from the omnipresent law enforcement
authorities.
   ``If we danced, the cops would shackle our wrists,'' he said. He
did not want his surname used.
   Groups of stern-looking police officers were intermingled with
the audience, while men with German shepherd dogs stood in the back.
   Coffin, who delivered some remarks in Russian between rock
songs, wasn't supposed to be the chief draw from ``the West.'' He
was supposed to play second fiddle to the peculiar British rocker,
Boy George.
   Boy George never showed up, but the show went on, featuring
primarily Russian pop and ``heavy metal'' groups.
   The event was sponsored by the Soviet Peace Committee. A
spokeswoman for that group said Boy George ``just didn't come.''
She gave no further explanation.
   The concert was held in Gorky Park, a spacious area with acres
of green trees and gardens and one of the most popular outdoor
spots in Moscow. It was billed as part of an effort to promote
peace between the superpowers.
   About 18,000 young people listened to blaring rhythm from giant
amplifiers on both sides of the stage as bright colored lights
flashed overhead, even though Moscow stays light until about 11
p.m. in May. On stage, performers with spiked, dyed hair and
fluorescent outfits danced with their electric guitars.
   ``This is a festival put on for the Reagan visit,'' said Leni, a
young Russian woman.
   There was none of the frenzied behavior common at American
concerts, and no sign of beer, alcohol or drugs. A lone vendor sold
juice and bread outside the entrance.
   For a group of American students from Texas A&M, the concert was
a chance to see their Soviet counterparts and enjoy a balmy
evening. ``People have been very nice to us,'' said Laura Hauss,
21, of Austin, Texas.
   While the Soviets were eager to meet Americans and trade chewing
gum for popular lapel pins, they were a little cautious about their
actions.
   ``They are allowed to talk with us, but they are still
reserved,'' said Matthew Stellges of San Antonio, Texas. The Texas
students are spending four weeks studying Russian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
