<HEAD>Soviet Bible a Hot Commodity</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lede and grafs 2, 4 and 6 to uppercase Bible</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The quickest-selling item in Moscow Saturday may
have been the 20 Russian Bibles that went on sale _ briefly, at $50
each _ at a booth at the international press center set up for the
U.S.-Soviet summit.
   Vladimir, a 34-year-old engineer who asked that his surname not
be used, said it was the first time he had seen a Bible on sale in
Moscow, although he had read one while a university student. The
Bible, however, is not taught in school.
   ``I have never see a Bible in a store anywhere in my life,'' he
said. The bibles were printed by the Moscow patriarchy.
   The Bibles were gone within minutes after they were put on
display at a booth that also sold religious records. A crowd of
people surrounded the booth, pressing to get hold of the book.
   Each one sold for 35 rubles, about $50.
   Bibles are a rarity in the Soviet Union where the official
policy has discouraged religion. But Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev recently met with Russian Orthodox leaders to intensify a
dialogue between church and state.
   Bibles were confiscated by customs agents when people attempted
to bring them into the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. and Soviets Said In Agreement on Fisheries Compact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev are expected next week to sign an agreement that will
allow Americans for the first time to fish in Soviet waters.
   The agreement also would require joint efforts to conserve and
manage Bering Sea fisheries.
   ``We reached agreement in principle two days ago in Moscow,''
said Ed Wolfe, the State Department's ambassador for oceans and
fisheries. ``It will be signed during the summit.''
   Wolfe declined to say when the signing was scheduled during the
Moscow summit, which begins Sunday. He spoke by telephone from his
Washington, D.C., office and said he had just returned Thursday
night from Moscow.
   The 10-page pact is a final version of a tentative agreement
reached by the two countries in February.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Removes Doubts Of U.S. Respect For Finnish Neutrality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Among the broader issues of peace and
human rights, President Reagan's gesture toward non-aligned Finland
was lost.
   Except to the Finns.
   In a policy speech Friday in Helsinki, Reagan removed lingering
doubts about the U.S. regard for neutrality in Finland, the only
non-communist country in Europe to sign a friendship treaty with
the Soviet Union.
   Politicians and newspapers hailed Reagan's speech as a
long-awaited authoritative acknowledgement of Finland's status in
the no-man's-land of international politics.
   Reagan said: ``America respects Finland's neutrality. We support
Finland's independence. We honor Finland's courageous history. We
salute the creative statesmanship that has been Finland's gift to
world peace.''
   ``We are naturally very satisfied with Reagan's evaluation of
Finland and the achievement of its foreign policy,'' Mati
Kahiluoto, chief of the Foreign Ministry's political department,
told the Hufvudstadsbladet daily.
   The speech ``gave the best possible recognition to Finland's
neutrality without overdoing it with flattery,'' said Paavo
Lipponen of the Social Democrats, Finland's largest party.
</TEXT>
