<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-Refuseniks     05-28 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Refuseniks,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Refuseniks Plan Daily Demonstrations During Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish refuseniks are planning to demonstrate
daily during the Moscow summit to protest Soviet human rights
policy and the denials of their requests to leave the country.
   Many well-known Jewish activists have been allowed to emigrate
from the Soviet Union under Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev,
leaving behind many others who have applied to leave.
   After Gorbachev came to power in March 1985, ``it seemed like
his reforms would solve the problem,'' said one of the activists,
Marina Durnovo.
   But lately the West has been paying less attention to the
problems of the activists, called refuseniks because they have been
refused permission to emigrate.
   Since the summit in Washington last December, ``the refusals
have been pounded down like hail,'' said Durnova.
   In planning to demonstrate during the summit, she said, ``our
aim is to draw the attention of the Soviet and American people to
the problem of Jewish emigration.''
   The U.S.-based National Conference on Soviet Jewry reported last
week that 1,086 Jews were allowed to leave the Soviet Union in
April, the highest monthly total in nearly seven years.
   The figure has been rising for about a year, but it falls far
short of the 1979 levels, when the monthly average was about 4,000
departures.
   Another activist, Yuri Semenovsky, said he had conducted a
survey of some of the estimated 2 million Jews in the Soviet Union
and concluded that 30 percent of them would like to leave. His
study appeared in the March issue of ``Referendum,'' an independent
journal published by the ``Press Club Glasnost,'' a dissident
organization that tests the limits of Gorbachev's reforms.
   Semenovsky said that 200,000 Jews had already applied to leave
the country and that many, like himself, had been harassed by the
authorities and forced out of their jobs and that many others were
afraid to ask.
   Members of the group disagreed on whether Gorbachev's reforms
had a positive overall effect. ``It is only cosmetic,'' said
Durnova.
   Semenovsky, in contrast, said that because of the reforms, ``the
barrier of fear had been lowered. People are not as afraid as they
were,'' he said, attributing the change to Gorbachev's policy of
greater openness.
   That same openness, however, has unleashed forces which some
Jewish activists view with fear. The ``Pamyat Society,'' a group of
ardent Russian nationalists who have become active under glasnost,
have voiced anti-Semitic sentiments, he said.
   Semenovsky's group has held 15 demonstrations this year, and
during the summit plans three more, all at the Lenin library in
downtown Moscow at 6 p.m. Some of the demonstrators have been
detained by police and fined for breaking the law, he said.
   No members of the group, which met with Western reporters on the
eve of President Reagan's arrival in Moscow on Sunday, were
scheduled to meet with the president during his stay.
   About a dozen Jewish activists were included in a group of
dissidents scheduled to meet with Reagan on Monday, the refuseniks
said.
   Among those expected to meet with Reagan were: Yuri and Tatyana
Zieman, Yuli Gosharovsky, Vladimir Kislik and his wife Bella Gulko,
Emil Lurie, Benjamen Charny, Igor Uspenski, his wife Ina Ioffe,
Roald Zelichenik, Yevgeny Linein and Emil Lurie, according to Yuri
Zieman and Semenovsky.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
