<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru   05-28 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0544,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Offer to Discuss Political Reforms With Contras</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Sandinista offer. Edits to
trim. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government said
today it was willing to discuss some of the political reforms the
rebels are demanding as a condition for ending the 6{-year-old
civil war.
   Defense Minister Gen. Humberto Ortega, head of the government
delegation at peace talks, said the offer was put before the rebel
leaders as the two sides resumed their discussions for a third day.
   The government asked rebel leaders to stay on and continue the
talks through the weekend, but the rebel leaders refused and said
they had to leave by the end of the day.
   The Sandinista offer included, with some rewording, nine
proposals from the U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras. These
included calls for political pluralism, equality before the law,
the right to strike and a pluralistic electoral system.
   The government offer reworked Contra demands for the separation
of state powers and the elimination of the state identification
with the ruling Sandinista National Liberation Front.
   The Sandinista negotiators also offered to discuss ``norms and
guarantees for the functioning of a system of mixed economy,
including the different forms of ownership.''
   All of this, Ortega said, would be discussed in a national
dialogue after a permanent cease-fire takes effect.
   Ortega said there had been ``considerable progress'' made during
the talks.
   ``We are going to the meeting hoping we can persuade them,''
Ortega told reporters.
   The negotiators were expected to agree on an extension of a
temporary cease-fire, paving the way for further peace talks at a
future meeting.
   Luis Rivas Leiva, a member of the Contra delegation, said there
were only five minor points to discuss in dealing with the
procedures for the truce extension and administration of areas
where the rebels have been gathered since the start of a two-month
cease-fire. That truce ends Monday.
   ``Then we can go on to discuss the more difficult aspects of the
political topics,'' he said.
   He said that would include the political conditions demanded by
the Contras for them to return to the ``political life of the
country'' and a permanent cease-fire.
   Contra leaders on Friday rejected a government proposal to
continue the latest round of peace talks past today's deadline and
said an agreement could be signed immediately if the leftist
government really wanted one.
   Meanwhile, one of the best-known commanders of the U.S.-backed
Contra rebels ended his struggle against the Sandinista government
and said he would encourage his troops to do the same.
   Felix Garcia Hernandez, known as Alfa Lima, told reporters
Friday that before he sought amnesty he commanded more than 400
Contra fighters in the central Chontales region of Nicaragua.
   Alfa Lima's action was the latest in a series of political
defeats suffered by the beleaguered guerrillas.
   Alfa Lima abandoned the rebel force with six of his men on
Wednesday. He said he hoped to encourage more of his former
comrades to take advantage of the amnesty.
   ``I am going to try to convince my men to come in. There are
many out there who do not know what they are doing or why they are
fighting,'' said the soft-spoken Alfa Lima, still wearing his
camouflage uniform.
   Alfa Lima's former commander-in-chief, Enrique Bermudez, in
Managua for the peace talks, said he regretted the officer's
decision.
   ``He was a field commander with a long record. We consider him a
war casualty,'' Bermudez said.
</TEXT>
