<DOCNO> AP880528-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 1332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-IwoJimaVet Bjt   05-28 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iwo Jima Vet, Bjt,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Survivor Recalls First Flag Raising Recalled</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHFIELD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 43 years, Charles W. Lindberg has
looked at photos of himself and five other Marines raising an
American flag on Iwo Jima in the prelude to one of the most
celebrated moments of World War II.
   Lindberg was part of the first flag-raising on the tiny Japanese
island, an event few know about besides the men who were there.
   About four hours later, a second flag was hoisted on Mount
Suribachi. That moment was immortalized by Associated Press
photographer Joe Rosenthal in a Pulitzer Prize-winning photo.
   Lindberg wasn't part of THE photo, but he's not jealous of those
who were.
   ``I'd rather be in this one than I would the second. This is a
true picture,'' said Lindberg, pointing to himself in one of his
many photos of the first flag-raising. ``Ours is the genuine
thing.''
   Lindberg, 67, a retired electrician, lives with his wife,
Violet, in a Minneapolis suburb. He has a roomful of books, photos
and mementos of Iwo Jima.
   The Grand Forks, N.D., native enlisted in the Marines in January
1942 at age 21. Three years later, a corporal, Lindberg went to Iwo
Jima as a member of the 28th Regiment of the 5th Marine Division.
   Iwo Jima, only eight miles square, was a strategic piece of land
750 miles south of Tokyo, and the United States wanted it to
support long-range B-29 bombers and a possible invasion of Japan.
   On Feb. 19, 1945, 30,000 Marines landed on the southeast coast.
More than 6,800 U.S. servicemen died in the five-week battle that
followed, and the 21,000-man Japanese defense force was virtually
wiped out.
   Lindberg's squad was in the spearhead of the attack on
Suribachi, at 546 feet the highest point on the island. It wasn't
far from the beach where the Marines landed, but it took four days
to climb.
   Lindberg remembers the Feb. 23 flag-raising as if it were
yesterday.
   ``When we reached the top of that mountain, about 10:30 in the
morning, we thought we were going to be in a lot of trouble,''
Lindberg said.
   ``First thing was, get the flag up. A couple of guys found a
water pipe up there. They had water systems, I guess. We tied the
flag to that pole and we carried it to the tallest place we could
find and we raised it.''
   It was the first time an American flag had flown over Japanese
territory. Lou Lowery, a photographer for the Marine magazine,
Leatherneck, took pictures of the men raising the flag on a 20-foot
pole.
   ``That's when everything broke loose,'' he said. ``The troops
down below began to cheer, and ship whistles out in the bay began
to toot. I tell you, it just made you shiver all over. I don't know
if it was pride or patriotism or what it was. What a feeling that
was. I'll never forget that.
   ``But right away, boom! I think the Japanese started to come out
of the caves,'' Lindberg said. ``So then we had to go after them.
Right away.''
   Lt. Col. Chandler W. Johnson ordered another, larger flag.
Meanwhile, Rosenthal was climbing the mountain. In an interview
from his San Francisco home, Rosenthal, 76, remembered how he ran
into Lowery coming down.
   Lowery laughed and said, ``I already got pictures up there. You
guys are late.''
   Rosenthal kept going, and bullets were still flying when he
captured the prize-winning image of five Marines and a Navy medical
corpsman driving the new flag into the ground.
   ``His (Lowery's photo) was 10 times more arduous to get than
mine,'' Rosenthal said. ``There may be some question which of the
two of us is the better photographer. However, there can be no
doubt which of us is luckier.''
   Of the six Marines who raised the original flag, only Lindberg,
1st Lt. Harold Schrier and Pfc. James Michaels returned from the
bloody battle alive.
   Lindberg's war ended on March 1, when a bullet shattered his
right forearm.
   Sgt. Ernest Thomas, Sgt. Henry Hansen and Pfc. Louis Charlo died
on the island. Schrier died in the 1970s, Michaels two years ago,
and Lowery died last year, Lindberg said.
   That makes Lindberg the sole surviving member of the crew.
   ``I think it was quite a thing to be, what I did. But you never
do it alone,'' Lindberg said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
