<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 1356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghan-Refugees     05-28 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Refugees,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Envoy Urges Superpowers to Help Rebuild Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The special U.N. envoy for Afghan
refugees urged the United States and Soviet Union on Saturday to
help repair the destruction wrought in Afghanistan by a decade of
civil war.
   ``I extend an appeal to Reagan and Gorbachev that they come
together and give the United Nations multilateral means to restore
the country that has been virtually destroyed by 10 years of
warfare,'' Prince Sadruddin Aga Khan said on a one-day visit to the
Afghan capital.
   President Reagan and Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the Soviet leader,
begin a summit Sunday in Moscow. Sadruddin urged the leaders to use
the summit to support U.N. humanitarian programs in Afghanistan.
   Sadruddin said a successful humanitarian aid program could be
the key to peace in Afghanistan, where Moslem guerrillas began
fighting after a Communist coup in April 1978. Soviet soldiers, who
entered the country in December 1979, began withdrawing May 15
under an agreement mediated by the United Nations.
   The prince warned against a hasty return of more than 5 million
Afghan refugees who fled to neighboring Pakistan and Iran to escape
the war.
   ``It would be very tragic if people were to rush back in a
disorganized way,'' Sadruddin said at the end of his day in Kabul,
the first stop on a tour that will include Pakistan and Iran.
   ``We have to prepare for the refugees' return,'' he said. ``If
they have no life support system, no crops, no food, no shelter,
there will be very little hope of encouraging voluntary return.
What can be done in Afghan humanitarian assistance today can be the
glue for peace.''
   Sadruddin was U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees in the 1970s.
He is the uncle of the Aga Khan, hereditary leader of the Ismaili
sect of Islam, which has adherents in Pakistan and Afghanistan as
well as other Asian and Middle Eastern nations.
   The sound of artillery fire boomed across the mountains girding
Kabul a few minutes before his news conference at the airport.
   He did not set a timetable or a cost for returning the refugees
to Afghanistan.
   Four days before the Soviet withdrawal began, Sadruddin was
named the U.N. Special Coordinator for Humanitarian and Economic
Assistance to Afghanistan.
   During his brief time in Kabul he met Afghan leader Najib and
new Prime Minister Hasan Sharq, who has led Afghanistan's efforts
to repatriate refugees.
   Accompanying the prince were representatives of the Red Cross
and the Red Crescent, its Islamic equivalent, and of several U.N.
agencies, including World Health Organization and UNICEF, the U.N.
Children's Fund.
   U.N. programs for refugees ``must be free of political strings
and should not be used as a weapon,'' Sadruddin said.
   The United States has supplied weapons to Afghan guerrillas
operating from bases in Pakistan and has reserved the right to do
so as long as the Soviet Union supplies the Afghan army.
   If all Afghan refugees living abroad return home, it will be the
biggest repatriation in U.N. history. About one-third of
Afghanistan's pre-war population now lives outside the country.
   According to figures cited by U.N. official Geneva last month,
there are 3.1 million Afghan refugees in Pakistan and 2.4 million
in Iran.
</TEXT>
