<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     05-28 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0799</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Duchess of York's polo-playing father, Maj.
Ronald Ferguson, was nearly dumped from the sport's ruling body
over allegations that he frequented prostitutes, the organization
said Saturday.
   The Hurlingham Polo Association, which governs the sport
throughout the British Commonwealth, voted down a resolution 7-6
that the 56-year-old major ``should be invited to tender his
resignation voluntarily,'' Brig. Peter Thwaites told The Associated
Press.
   Thwaites, chairman of the stewards committee, said he was among
those pressing for Ferguson's resignation as an association steward.
   ``I'm not for a moment saying we are all whiter than white. But
you can't really have a chap sitting in judgment over somebody else
who has, by his own confession, behaved badly,'' Thwaites said.
   The Sunday People, a mass-circulation tabloid, published a photo
on May 8 of Ferguson leaving the Wigmore Club, a London massage
parlor. It quoted prostitutes as saying he was ``one of their most
valued regular customers.''
   Ferguson was quoted at the time as dismissing the claim without
denying it, and has since refused to comment.
   Ferguson is a retired officer of Queen Elizabeth II's household
cavalry and is polo manager to her son and heir Prince Charles.
Ferguson's daughter Sarah is married to Prince Andrew, the queen's
second son.
   The resignation demand came up at a meeting of the association's
stewards committee Tuesday.
   ``I thought the honorable thing was for him to resign,''
Thwaites said. ``But he argued he had a great deal of support from
his family and friends and he didn't want to be ground down by what
he called the `gutter press'.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carroll Bing, the wife of former Metropolitan
Opera impresario Sir Rudolf Bing, ``has lost touch with reality,''
says her lawyer, who won a request in court that she undergo a
psychiatric examination.
   Harvey Sladkus asked state Supreme Court Justice Carmen Ciparick
to order that Lady Bing, a 48-year-old former mental patient, be
hospitalized and medicated ``for as long as necessary.''
   The Manhattan judge agreed Friday that a psychiatric exam was
warranted.
   ``I'm of the firm opinion that Lady Bing doesn't know what's
going on and cannot understand the court's mandates,'' Sladkus
said. ``She's disoriented and bewildered. She's frightened and
confused.
   ``We're seeing the disintegration of a human life.''
   Ciparick cited as examples reports that she had violated the
court's orders to leave her husband alone at certain hours and
reports she was arrested for allegedly assaulting one of her
86-year-old husband's nurses Tuesday night.
   Millard Midonick, Bing's court-appointed guardian, said he
expects tests of both Bing and Lady Bing to get under way early
this week. Bing suffers from Alzheimer's disease.
   Bing's lawyer, Paul Goldhamer, wants the marriage annulled. He
says Lady Bing has abused her husband verbally and physically, and
Bing did not know what he was doing when he married Lady Bing in
Arlington, Va., on Jan. 9, 1987.
   Goldhamer said that 15 seconds after his client agreed to marry
Lady Bing, he asked her, ``But dear, won't you tell me your name?''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mae Boren Axton, who co-wrote the Elvis
Presley song ``Heartbreak Hotel,'' has helped raise more than
$18,000 for the financially strapped Nashville Symphony Orchestra.
   Ms. Axton, who now runs her own public relations agency, said
Friday that the money came from friends concerned about the
orchestra's plight. It was disbanded in February because of lack of
funds, leaving the town known as ``Music City USA'' without a
symphony.
   Ms. Axton made the donation to a musician's group, the Nashville
Symphony Players Assembly. Ms. Axton is the mother of Hoyt Axton, a
singer-songwriter-actor.
</TEXT>
