<DOCNO> AP880528-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 1431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthAfrica-Bomb 1stLd-Writethru   05-28 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0565,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explosion Reportedly Injures One; Three Killed in Shooting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with three killed in separate
shooting, NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded Saturday at
Johannesburg's main railroad station, and radio reports said one
woman was injured.
   Near the city of Durban, three blacks were killed when five men
with shotguns opened fire on a house in a black township, police
said.
   Police confirmed the Johannesburg blast but said no further
details were available.
   The blast came two days after bombings in Pretoria injured four
white women. Those blasts coincided with the 40th anniversary of
the governing Nationalist Party's rise to power.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok blamed the Pretoria bombings
on the outlawed African National Congress guerrilla movement, the
main group fighting to topple South Africa's white-led government.
   In South Africa, the 26 million blacks have no voice in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate schools, districts and health services.
   The shooting victims near the southeastern city of Durban were
members of a family that had participated in a wedding Friday
evening in Shongwni township, police said.
   The 17-year-old brother of the bride was among those killed,
police said. They said the bride's mother was seriously wounded.
   Police said they were investigating but had not determined the
motive for the attack. The township has been the scene of black
factional fighting in recent weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
