<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Judge-Smoking 1stLd-Writethru a0559 05-28 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Judge-Smoking, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0559,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Woman To Quit Smoking</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to add name of woman, more details on conviction,
probation, reaction</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered a woman to stop
smoking, saying that she can't afford it because she has five
children and no job.
   Judge Leonard Hoffman, a two-pack-a-day smoker until he quit on
Oct. 15, 1956, said it was the first time he has ordered a
defendant to stop smoking.
   ``I'd probably do it again,'' said Hoffman, who describes
himself as ``a square.''
   Julie Weatherbee Lunceford was in court on a probation hearing,
the Greenville Herald-Banner reported Friday.
   ``She came to me pleading poverty and I don't know why, but I
said, `Do you smoke?' and she said, `Yes,' and I said, `How in the
world can you afford to? You said you don't have a job,''' Hoffman
said.
   ``The surgeon general said it's addictive, it's been publicly
declared an addiction. The woman said she had no job. Why should
the taxpaying public subsidize an addiction?''
   Lunceford, who is on welfare, was sentenced to five years
probation in 1983 for theft of cattle. She was accused of failing
to report to her probation officer for two years and Hoffman,
visiting from Dallas County, ordered her to resume reporting and
quit smoking in 30 days.
   He said it would be up to the Hunt County Adult Probation
Department to enforce his order.
   Lunceford's lawyer, Peter Chamberlain, said the 23-year-old
defendant was relieved by the no-smoking sentence since she could
have been sent to prison. Hoffman said he did not consider prison
because of her children.
</TEXT>
