<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CrackHouses     05-28 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crack Houses,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tampa Mayor Razes 50 Vacant Houses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bulldozers flattened 50 vacant city homes in
an attempt by the mayor's office to quash the crack problem, and
columns of smoke rose over the city from heaps of rubble ignited by
construction crews.
   ``It's a win-win situation,'' Mayor Sandy Freedman said Friday
as demolition crews finished three days of work. ``One lady who
lives near a house we tore down on Seventh Avenue called this
morning to say she'd slept better last night than she had in
years.''
   Of the 50 condemned structures on the mayor's list, a dozen were
known crack houses, and the others are likely to become centers of
criminal activity, a release from the mayor's office said. Crack is
a smokable form of cocaine.
   ``Any vacant house within a high drug area is a potential crack
house,'' said police Maj. Bert Hatcher.
   The campaign has adopted the slogan, ``Mayor's Crack Down.''
   ``I'll sure feel more safe getting in and out of my car when
this job is done,'' said Louise Brown, a teacher at a nursery.
   Meanwhile, fire officials arrested a man after he allegedly told
them he joined in on the destruction and set fire to a crack house.
   State fire investigator A. Alcala said he hated to arrest the
21-year-old John Marshall Aydelotte, but he had no choice after
Adyelotte described how he ignited a cardboard box Friday and
tossed it into one of three vacant houses.
   The resulting blaze consumed that building and heavily damaged
the other two. None of the three buildings was among the 50 slated
for destruction.
</TEXT>
