<HEAD>Actor Tells Magazine About Growing Up in Fredericksburg</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREDERICKSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Judge Reinhold hasn't forgotten
growing up in Fredericksburg, ``a little Southern town ... where
there was really all the time in the world with nothing to do. The
only recreation was mindless cruising.''
   ``My first car was a '63 Chevy station wagon that I called
Ramona, because that's the sound it made. `FARM USE' was painted on
the back. It was right off the set of `Hee Haw,''' Reinhold said,
according to the July issue of Playboy magazine.
   He said Marines stationed at the nearby Quantico base ``would
drive up behind me and my long-haired friends at red lights and
start screaming sexual come-ons at us. Some of them, even after we
turned around, thought we were just ugly girls.''
   Reinhold, 30, said he was the ``Alan Alda'' of his class at
James Monroe High School _ the kind of guy girls could talk to
about their boyfriend problems.
   Among Reinhold's movie credits since leaving Fredericksburg are
``Fast Times at Ridgemont High,'' ``Ruthless People,'' ``Beverly
Hills Cop'' and ``Vice Versa.''
