<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     05-28 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GILBERTSVILLE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took six planes and 22 parachute
packers, but Dale Nelson has set what he thinks is a record _ 301
dives in less than 24 hours, about 4{ minutes per jump.
   He said he completed the feat Friday, which raised thousands of
dollars for four charities, with no fear and no stress.
   Witnesses said Nelson completed 301 consecutive skydives between
5 p.m. Thursday and about 3:30 p.m. Friday, surpassing the mark of
250 listed by the Guinness Book of World Records.
   ``I'm not that tired. It was an adrenaline rush all 24 hours,''
Nelson, 38 and a father of two teen-agers, said in a telephone
interview shortly after completing jump No. 301.
   Over and over again, Nelson would ride an airplane to 2,000
feet, jump out and parachute to a landing, take off the used
`chute, strap on a freshly packed one, and climb on another waiting
airplane.
   With a crew of pilots and 22 parachute packers, Nelson, a
291-jump veteran before the record attempt, said he never feared
for his safety.
   ``It was 100 percent trust _ zero stress,'' he said.
   David Huber, of Issaquah, Wash., set the 250-jump mark over the
Fourth of July weekend in 1985. Nelson's jumps won't be noted as a
record until the Guinness editors verify the feat through
interviews with witnesses, according to David Boehm, American
editor for Guinness.
   Nelson, of Bryn Mawr, received $26,000 in cash and pledges
before he started jumping and has gathered more money through
donations, parking fees and sales of $10 T-shirts to the roughly
1,000 people who dropped by the New Hanover Airport to watch, said
Nelson's sister, Judy Nelson.
   Ms. Nelson said she and her brother had budgeted about $16,000
of the money for expenses, but many pilots and parachute packers
donated their time.
   ``I'd guess it will be about half that. We'll have to pay for
gasoline and some plane expense,'' she said.
   Nelson reserved six airplanes, with only two in use at any one
time, his sister said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HINTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Graduation is a family affair for the
Simmses, with mother, father and daughter all getting diplomas from
different schools in a three-week period.
   Mary Simms of Hinton graduated from Concord College on May 14.
Her husband, Ralph, is in line for a degree Saturday from the West
Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine at Lewisburg. Their
daughter, Susan, graduates Friday from Hinton High School.
   Susan's graduation announcements listed all three graduates, but
her parents say they're not trying to steal the spotlight.
   ``We tried to give everybody equal billing,'' Mrs. Simms said.
``We know graduation is an important time for Susan. We are not
taking away from her attention. She's still the one getting the
gifts.''
   In fact, Susan said her unusual situation is getting her more
attention that the average high school graduate.
   ``All my friends at school think it's pretty neat that we're
doing it at the same time,'' she said.
