<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0618 05-28 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0618,500</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 1-2 to correct spelling of `comedian.' SUBS 15th
graf to spell out Home Box Office. Note language 13th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis traded jokes with comedians Robin
Williams and Billy Crystal on Saturday, but when the humor started
to turn off-color, the Democratic presidential front-runner
jokingly told Williams to tone it down.
   The two comedians were presenting a $217,000 check for homeless
assistance to a Boston health care group.
   Handing the check to Boston Mayor Raymond L. Flynn, Crystal
said: ``You'll need two forms of ID if you have them. But hold it
till Thursday.''
   The exchange took place at a Statehouse ceremony in which the
Boston Health Care for the Homeless Project received the check from
Comic Relief, a organizations formed by 80 comedians in 1986 which
has raised $4.7 million for the homeless in 23 cities nationwide.
   ``Speaking of comic relief, we had some yesterday,'' Dukakis
said.
   ``The vice president said his cholesterol level was going up. He
was angry and his cholesterol level was going up. I wonder what he
meant by that.''
   Dukakis got a laugh, but Crystal got a bigger one.
   ``Too much fat in the budget,'' he said.
   ``You can use that. I think it'll work,'' Crystal added, turning
to Dukakis. ``But you've got to give it some punch.''
   ``We are delighted to be here to celebrate the cholesterol level
of Mr. Bush and the rising formaldehyde level of President
Reagan,'' Crystal said. ``We met at this hour because Mercury and
Jupiter were in perfect alignment.''
   Williams said he had yet to perfect an impersonation of Dukakis,
but he did step forward and with an upbeat voice and choppy
delivery characteristic of the governor.
   ``I'm working on it right now because I'm feeling really good
about it. I haven't got it yet but I hope too soon.
   ``If he gets into the White House, his ass will be on the
line,'' Williams said.
   When Williams made one off-color remark that was a play on
astrological and anatomical terms, Dukakis told him to stop it.
   ``This is not HBO (Home Box Office),'' the Massachusetts
governor said. ``This is the governor's press conference.''
   Dukakis took the opportunity to charge the Reagan administration
with failing to build adequate housing for the nation's homeless
and pledged to reverse the trend if elected.
   He said state funding for the homeless had increased to $166
million from $11.8 million in the last five years and the
Legislature has authorized more than $1 billion for construction of
affordable housing for working and low-income families.
   ``There's only one reason today we have homeless people in
America,'' Dukakis said. ``It's because we aren't building
affordable housing for people of low and moderate income. It's as
simple as that.
   ``If all goes well this fall we're going to start building
affordable housing for families and businesses of low and moderate
income.''
</TEXT>
