<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UCLAMelee     05-28 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UCLA Melee,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Melee, Guard Planned For Rescheduled UCLA Student Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After student protesters overturned ballot
boxes, upended polling booths and exchanged blows with workers
during a student election, UCLA officials said a rescheduled vote
will be heavily guarded.
   Winston Doby, vice chancellor of student affairs at the
University of California, Los Angeles, said Friday the school was
investigating Thursday's melee and was exploring the possibility of
disciplinary action.
   A group of about 200 mostly minority students marched on polling
places after a heated rally protesting the disqualification of a
Hispanic candidate, Lloyd Monserratt, for student body president.
   ``I've never seen, in my history at UCLA, students disrupt a
free and open election,'' Doby said. ``Whenever you have a
challenge to the free and open electoral process, you have to view
that as a very critical and serious problem because that principle
underlies a free democracy.''
   No arrests or serious injuries were reported.
   Some Monserratt supporters contended his disqualification, after
he won the campus primary three weeks ago, was racially motivated.
   Monserratt was removed from the ballot by the school's student
governing body, the Undergraduate Student Association Council,
because of a sub-par grade point average and a lack of college
credits, Doby said.
   He blamed the disqualification for the election fracas, and
admitted racial tensions exist on the campus.
   ``I think there's no question that in our student politics,
there is racial tension,'' Doby said.
   The student council nullified last Thursday's voting because
some ballots were stolen by protesters.
   The new vote will take place next Thursday under heavy guard by
campus police, Doby said.
   Nearly 44 percent of the school's 23,000 undergraduates are
black, Hispanic or Asian, the highest level of minority enrollment
in campus history, Doby said.
   ``One might argue that our increased tension is an indication of
our success'' at bringing minorities into the student population,
Doby said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
