<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-Refuseniks     05-28 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Refuseniks,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Women Demonstrate Against Soviet Policy Toward Jews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MALMO, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small group of demonstrators appealed to
Moscow on Saturday to let 11 Jewish women emigrate, police said.
   The 11 women said they would carry out hunger strikes during
this week's superpower summit, a news agency said.
   A police officer who spoke on condition of anonymity said 18
women took part in the peaceful demonstration in the southern port
of Malmo.
   The national news agency TT quoted unidentified activists as
saying that some of the Soviet Jews had been applying for permits
to go to Israel since 1971.
   The agency said the activists had sent an appeal to Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and told him that the 11 women planned
hunger strikes in Moscow and Leningrad during the Moscow summit,
which begins Sunday.
   TT said the activists also sent a copy of their letter to Reagan.
</TEXT>
