<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Norwegian     05-28 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Norwegian,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Norwegan Relief Group Evacuates Foreign Personnel From South
Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Norwegian relief group evacuated its
foreign personnel from south Lebanon ``for security reasons''
Saturday, one week after a Belgian volunteer disappeared.
   ``We cannot continue sending medical volunteers if they
disappear like Dr. Jan Cools,'' the Norwac group said in a
statement.
   The relief group did not say how many people were involved in
the evacuation.
   Cools, 32, has worked with Norwac for three months. He vanished
May 21 after leaving the Rashidiyeh Palestinian refugee camp near
the southern city of Tyre.
   The statement said Cools was heading for a U.N. peacekeeping
force base in Tyre to pick up his mail when he disappeared.
   Police said they have no information about his disappearance,
and no one has claimed responsibility.
   However, Rashidiyeh administrators said Thursday that Cools had
been kidnapped by unidentified gunmen at a road junction near Tyre.
It gave no details.
   There are 18 foreigners, including nine Americans, missing in
Lebanon after being kidnapped. Most are believed held by Shiite
Moslem groups linked to the pro-Iranian Hezbollah militia.
   The hostage held longest is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
