<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GuerrillaMugging     05-28 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guerrilla Mugging,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kurdish Guerrillas Attack Climbers on Ararat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGRI, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A band of Kurdish guerrillas mugged a group
of foreign climbers on Mount Ararat, burned their camping equipment
and stole their cameras and money, the Anatolia News Agency
reported Saturday.
   The agency said the climbers _ one from Belgium, one from West
Germany, and two from France _ were descending with three Turkish
guides after a climb to the 17,000-foot peak when they encountered
the assailants at an altitude of 10,500 feet.
   Budolf Richter, the Belgian, told the agency there were four,
heavily armed men.
   The government temporarily banned climbing the mountain two
years ago for security reasons following other such incidents.
   Most of the guerrillas operating in the region are linked to the
Kurdish Labor Party, which seeks to set up a Marxist state in parts
of eastern and southeastern Turkey.
   Nearly 900 civilians and military personnel and an equal number
of Kurdish insurgents have been killed since Kurdish guerrillas
started hit-and-run attacks in 1984.
   Ethnic Kurds make up about one-fifth of Turkey's population of
52 million.
</TEXT>
