<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 1645EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Pregnancy-SecretDrugs     05-28 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pregnancy-Secret Drugs,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 200 Pregnant Women Given Drugs Without Consent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 pregnant women may have unknowingly
taken a drug as part of a study conducted by two Cook County
Hospital physicians, the hospital's director says.
   The study was to determine if Dilantin, a common drug used to
treat epilepsy and stroke patients, could reduce fetal stress in
cases of Caesarean section births, said Terrence Hansen, the
hospital's director.
   About 245 pregnant women were given the drug by two
anesthesiologists between late September 1987 and Jan. 16, but an
initial review showed that just five of the women signed consent
forms to be part of the study, Hansen said late Friday.
   ``It is against hospital policies not to obtain the patients'
signed consent,'' Hansen said in a telephone interview. ``In this
case, they did not.''
   Hansen said he knew of no injuries caused by the administration
of the Dilantin, which he characterized as a common drug.
   ``The dosages were small,'' he said. ``It's very, very unlikely
... that there were side effects or detrimental effects.''
   Hansen declined to identify the two doctors, but said the
recommended punishment was probation, a warning that could lead to
disciplinary measures by the hospital if the doctors commit further
policy violations.
   He said two babies born to the 245 mothers died, but he said
both deaths resulted from complications because of ``significant
prematurity.'' He said autopsies performed ruled out a link to the
Dilantin.
   The hospital is run by the county and is on the city's
economically depressed West Side.
   The study was approved by a hospital physicians' committee in
September, but after a routine review of the research, the issue of
the consent forms was raised, according to Hansen.
   The hospital's Executive Medical Staff, a group of about 35
doctors, last week recommended one year of probation for the two
doctors involved, Hansen said.
   The final word on what punishment, if any, will be applied is up
to the Cook County Board, which acts as the hospital's board of
trustees, Hansen said. The board next meets June 6, he said.
   The drug most likely would have been administered intravenously,
he said.
   Hansen could not say if all of the women who were given the drug
were candidates for Caesarean section births. He said hospital
officials were conducting their own review of patient records in
the case.
   Hansen also said he did not know the status of the research.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
