<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0612 05-28 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0612,790</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: New thruout with comments from Sununu and Thompson on Bush
mapping new strategy; EDITS to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush will part company with
President Reagan on a variety of domestic issues in a campaign that
will also portray Democrat Michael Dukakis' management record as a
failed one, two Republican governors said Saturday.
   Govs. John Sununu of New Hampshire and James Thompson of
Illinois told reporters that Bush was working to develop a package
of new proposals on child care, the homeless, housing, education
and drug education.
   ``The vice president is a man firmly committed to setting his
own agenda. I don't think there was any doubt about that at all,''
Thompson said after two days of strategy meetings at Bush's
oceanside vacation retreat.
   Bush is meeting with Republican leaders and advisers during his
weeklong stay.
   Sununu said that ``the domestic side is going to be one of the
strong points of the Bush campaign and the Bush presidency'' in
contrast to what he said were ``management failures of the Dukakis
administration'' as governor of Massachusetts.
   Responding to Sununu's comments, Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach
said: ``If there weren't jobs in Massachusetts for the people who
lived in New Hampshire, the New Hampshire unemployment rate would
practically triple.''
   Dach said the Dukakis campaign would be happy to debate the
governor's economic record ``because when we do it reminds voters
that Mike Dukakis has a record of innovative accomplishments for
people and George Bush has seven years of silence on critical
domestic issues.''
   Sununu's comments signaled an apparent decision by Bush campaign
strategists to take on Dukakis directly on domestic policy issues,
usually considered his strong suit.
   Sununu cited ``an inability to handle the budget'' and alleged
failure of Dukakis to modernize the state's prison facilities or do
a better job in processing welfare payments for families with
dependent children.
   He also claimed the Dukakis administration had failed to project
future state spending levels carefully, raising prospects of
``hundreds of millions of dollar deficits'' if there is an economic
downturn.
   Sununu, a longtime Bush supporter, said that the vice
president's campaign would seek in the months ahead to show voters
``the difference of the reality of what (Dukakis) has done versus
the perception.''
   Thompson said that during the strategy session, Bush was given
guidence on ``what works and what doesn't work in the real world.''
   ``The bottom line is that George Bush wants to make the nation
work,'' Thompson said.
   Republican leaders have been urging Bush to put distance between
himself and Reagan, and Bush has been striking out in recent days
in an effort to do just that.
   Thompson and other participants at the weekend strategy and
issues sessions had few details of what the new Bush domestic
programs would contain. Thompson said they would be unveiled at the
appropriate time.
   During the meetings, Bush and his campaign aides also discussed
the problems of embattled Attorney General Edwin Meese III and the
fallout over failed negotiations with Panamanian leader Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   The troubles still hound Bush, as recent polls indicated that
likely Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis held a double-digit lead
over the vice president. Bush shrugs off the polling data, claiming
he likes being able to fight back as an underdog, but the results
have top campaign strategists worried.
   ``I've never been in a campaign when I wouldn't rather be ahead
than behind,'' says Bush pollster Robert Teeter.
   Meanwhile, an aide to Bush declined to comment on a report in
Saturday's editions of The Washington Post that Bush met privately
with Meese earlier this month to discuss political ramifications of
the attorney general's ongoing legal problems.
   Citing unidentified sources, the newspaper said it could not be
learned what Bush told Meese.
   Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., one of those invited to meet with Bush
in Maine, said a healthy economy and a diminished Soviet threat
have given social issues more importance in this year's
presidential campaign _ posing a problem not only to Bush but for
all Republicans.
   Democrats are generally identified with being more concerned
than Republicans on social issues, she said.
   ``The fact is, we're moving into the 1990s. Issues like day
care, which were not issues in 1980, are issues today when we see
50 percent of the women with children under three working. So you
don't have to move away from Ronald Reagan. You're just moving into
a new era,'' Ms. Martin said.
   It wasn't all work for the vice president. He has been taking
guests out for short rides in the Atlantic Ocean on his power boat,
``Fidelity.'' And on Monday, he planned to march in the annual
Kennebunkport Memorial Day parade.
</TEXT>
