<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama-Delvalle     05-28 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Delvalle,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deposed President Delvalle Hangs On To Claim To Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama-Blunders, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ousted president, Eric Arturo
Delvalle, waits in hiding to resume his job with Washington's
blessing, but the general who had him dismissed has stared down the
Colossus of the North and won't let go.
   The United States still recognizes Delvalle but apparently did
not push for his restoration to power in talks with Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, head of the military and de facto leader of
Panama. Those discussions on an arrangement for Noriega to step
down collapsed last week.
   Opposition groups have conducted low-key demonstrations
demanding that Noriega go, but little public sentiment has been
expressed about Delvalle.
   Delvalle himself, in a rare meeting with foreign journalists
last week, said there is no reason for him to surrender his claim
to the presidency.
   ``Why should I?'' he replied when asked if there were
circumstances under which he might abandon it.
   ``This is one of the basic factors: respect for the constitution
by the military,'' he said. ``All over Latin America there has been
a clear, loud message that (the military) are below civilian
government.
   ``Under no circumstances should it be considered that I resign
as president of the republic ... to satisfy the pride of Gen.
Noriega,'' he added.
   Delvalle tried to dismiss Noriega on Feb. 25 as commander of
Panama's army and police. The next day, Noriega supporters in the
National Assembly voted to dismiss Delvalle.
   U.S. federal courts indicted Noriega on drug trafficking charges
in July and Washington has imposed economic sanctions on Panama in
an attempt to oust him.
   More negotiations _ discussions, as the general calls them _ are
likely, this time with Latin American democracies taking part, and
other opposition leaders question whether they can or should go to
the mat for Delvalle.
   ``I believe all Panamanians who want a democracy must be willing
to contribute to the fight and to sacrifice positions when the
moment arrives,'' said Ricardo Arias Calderon, head of Panama's
Christian Democrat Party. ``This applies to all.''
   He and other opposition figures advocate a government of
``national conciliation'' that would bring various sectors together.
   Guillermo Endara of the largest opposition party, the Authentic
Panamenists, said Delvalle ``is probably not the person to solve
the Panamanian crisis at this time.''
   He said Delvalle, who comes from the small, business-oriented
Republican Party, does not have a broad base.
   Panamanian authorities issued an arrest warrant for Delvalle two
months ago but has made no evident effort to find him.
   Delvalle told journalists he has not left Panama since he went
into hiding shortly after he his dismissal, and denied living in
any embassy or on a military base. The United States maintains
military installations along the Panama Canal.
   Some members of his family stay at the residence of U.S.
Ambassador Arthur Davis, but embassy officials say Delvalle is not.
   The military seems adamant that Manuel Solis Palma, who replaced
Delvalle, remain as president. A tentative deal between the United
States and Noriega's negotiators was turned down because it did not
guarantee that he would remain in office.
</TEXT>
