<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Summit-Senate-INF 1stLd-Writethru a0552 05-28 0939</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Senate-INF, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0552,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders Say INF Scrutiny Shows Senate Will Carefully Scrutinize
Arms Pacts</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts 3 grafs after 3rd graf bgng: ``The Senate ... to
UPDATE with Baker departure and quotes. Picks up 4th graf pvs bgng:
The INF pact ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate's work on the medium-range missile
treaty shows that lawmakers will carefully scrutinize any arms pact
and not be just a rubber stamp for the president, say the chamber's
leaders.
   That theme was heard often during the two weeks of floor debate
on the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces (INF) treaty, ratified
Friday by a 93-5 vote, and is likely to continue for any future
arms agreements.
   ``The Senate has clearly made visible that it is an equal
partner with any president in the making of treaties,'' said Senate
Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va. ``And I hope that will be a
sobering impact on this president and Mr. Gorbachev when they sit
down and discuss another agreement.''
   White House chief of staff Howard H. Baker Jr., who left with
the treaty Saturday to join President Reagan in Helsinki, said the
ratified pact indicated a ``new spirit of bipartisan cooperation''
between the president and Congress.
   ``The president, I believe, has shown his dedication to peace,
his dedication to strength, his dedication to see he leaves a
legacy of a better world and a safer world at the end of his eight
years as president,'' Baker told reporters at Andrews Air Force
Base.
   There will be a ceremonial exchange of the treaty documents in
Moscow on Wednesday, and Baker said the exchange signaled ``a
historic improvement of the relationship of the two superpowers of
the world.''
   The INF pact ``in a lot of ways, was a stalking horse for
START,'' said Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, referring to the
proposed Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty.
   Both Cohen and Byrd noted that the INF was closely scrutinized
by three different committees. If the Senate learned anything from
its work on the treaty, Byrd said, ``it is that we have to ask a
lot of questions, that we have to look very closely.''
   ``We were very deliberative, we were very thorough and I believe
that we have improved this treaty,'' said Byrd. ``I think we've
closed all the loopholes we know about in this treaty and it's a
much better treaty than when it was sent'' to Capitol Hill.
   Byrd had pulled the INF treaty off the Senate's calendar due to
questions that were raised about whether the Soviet Union intended
to comply with all verification provisions.
   ``I resisted the pressure to bring up this treaty until the
faults could be corrected,'' said Byrd. ``The administration's
negotiators went back to Geneva and corrected those faults. It is
now a better treaty than it ever was before.''
   Cohen agreed, noting, ``I think that in some ways, we improved
the treaty. We tied down some loose ends that perhaps could have
caused trouble if we hadn't cleared them up.''
   But, Cohen asked, ``if we had this much debate and trouble on a
treaty like INF, just imagine what would happen if we get a START
treaty.''
   He noted that the INF pact was relatively straightforward and
involved only a small percentage of each superpower's atomic
arsenal. By contrast, a START agreement would reduce arsenals by 50
percent and would require far more extensive verification
provisions. It would thus permit far more opportunities to cheat.
   The biggest fight over the INF pact stemmed from a fight between
President Reagan and the Democratic-controlled Congress over the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty.
   Reagan asserts that his administration has the legal authority
to change the U.S. interpretation of the 1972 pact, a move that
would permit expanded tests of Reagan's Star Wars anti-missile
system. Congressional Democrats dispute that claim.
   The Senate approved an amendment to the INF ratification
resolution banning any future president from re-intepreting the
pact unless Congress first approves.
   ``What we learned from that is that you have to be very careful,
you have to be very sure, when you ratify a treaty,'' said Sen. Sam
Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Armed Services Committee and a chief
critic of the proposed change in the ABM pact.
   Byrd said the anti-interpretation amendment is ``a clear signal
to the administration, future administrations and the Soviets ...
that this Senate will not roll over and play dead ... and is not a
rubber stamp to any president.''
   But the suggestion that the Senate was an equal partner with the
president in the making of treaties brought a different response
from Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa.
   ``This is one of the most serious constitutional issues to come
before this body in a long time ... we are trampling on the
Constitution,'' he said.
   Reagan submitted the INF pact to the Senate on Jan. 25,
beginning an exhaustive review of the treaty by the Foreign
Relations, Armed Services and Intelligence committee.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., said the scrutiny
provided a ``model of how we should perform our role to advise and
consent to treaties. I think this the most closely examined arms
control treaty in history.''
   But Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., a critic of the INF pact,
continually decried what he termed ``this rush to judgment.''
   The INF pact was on the Senate floor for nine days, a far
shorter time than previous treaties, Helms noted.
   ``I think that any future treaty should be examined much more
closely, in much greater detail, than we have done with this
treaty. Our work here may well come back to haunt us,'' he said.
</TEXT>
