<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-28 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sunny and Warm in Most Central, Eastern States; Cold Front Dampens
Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunny skies and warm temperatures prevailed in much of the
country at the start of the Memorial Day weekend Saturday, but a
cold front ushered cool, wet weather into the northern Pacific
Coast region.
   The front brought showers and locally heavy rain into the area,
with temperatures in the upper 40s and 50s, and is expected to
spread cool, wet and windy weather into Western states over the
next couple of days, with snow expected at some higher elevations
of the mountains of northern California.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed in central Kansas and the
Red River Valley of Minnesota and North Dakota. Thunderstorms in
southeastern North Dakota dropped 1.75 inches of rain in an hour
around Edgeley early Saturday.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed across southern
Colorado and northern New Mexico, in southern Florida, in eastern
North Carolina and in southeastern Virginia.
   Sunny skies prevailed across much of the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures were in the 80s across most central and eastern
states, with readings approaching the 90-degree mark as far north
as Maine and North Dakota. Portland, Maine, set a record high for
the day of 89 degrees.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 46 degrees at Klamath
Falls, Ore., to 94 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Sunday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms in
southern and central Florida, and widely scattered storms in the
Great Plains. Showers and a few thunderstorms also were predicted
from the central and northern Pacific Coast to the central and
northern Plateau, with snow in some of the higher elevations. Fair
to partly sunny skies will prevail elsewhere, with strong and gusty
winds from the Southwest to Colorado and Wyoming.
   Highs were forecast to be in the upper 50s and 60s from the
central and northern Pacific Coast to the central and northern
Plateau, and along the southern Pacific Coast; in the 70s in New
England and the Great Lakes; and above 80 degrees elsewhere east of
the Rockies, with lower 90s in the north-central states. Highs also
were expected to be in the 80s and 90s in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
