<2ND_LINE>AM-Sea World-Shamu,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamu Balks During Debut</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Sea World</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamu, a three-ton killer whale that
is the main attraction of the new Sea World of Texas, showed his
animal trainers who really was the boss in the water Saturday.
   Shamu splashed his way around his 7-million-gallon tank,
frequently pushing water out of the tank onto spectators.
   But halfway through a lap around the pool, the killer whale
stopped and stared at the crowd through the glass tank.
   Trainers Laura Perkins and Mark McHugh decided to let him stop
and stare after the killer whale ignored several instructions to go
on with the show.
   ``I'm not going to try to tell a six-thousand-pound killer whale
what to do,'' McHugh said. ``He can do what he wants to do. We'll
just sit it out and wait for him.''
   They said the killer whale liked to play games with the
trainers, but that eventually it has to come up for air.
   After about seven minutes under water, Shamu decided he was
ready to play again. He gave his trainers a signal that he was
ready to proceed and went on with the rest of the 30-minute act.
</TEXT>
