<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 1834EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HughesInvestigated     05-28 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hughes Investigated,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Probes Allegations of Illegal Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hughes Aircraft is under investigation
because of allegations that it reaped millions of dollars in
improper profits on a 1983 TOW missile contract with the Army, a
newspaper reported Saturday.
   A federal grand jury in Birmingham, Ala., has subpoenaed 13
officials of the General Motors subsidiary since February along
with Executive Vice President D. Kenneth Richardson, who is to
testify soon, an unidentified company spokesman told the Los
Angeles Times.
   At least seven federal employees have appeared before the jury,
and recently appointed Hughes president Malcolm R. Currie was
interviewed by the U.S. attorney's office in Birmingham, the
newspaper reported.
   Currie was in charge of Hughes Missile Systems Group in Los
Angeles in 1983.
   The spokesman for the firm said the company denies any
wrongdoing involving the $120 million contract, which covered
production in 1983 and 1984.
   At issue is whether Hughes negotiated the deal without telling
the Army it anticipated cutting costs by transferring production of
missile wiring systems from a plant in Tucson, Ariz., to one in
Eufaula, Ala.
   If Hughes did anticipate the reduction and failed to tell the
Army, there may be a violation of the federal Truth in Negotiation
Act, the Times said.
   Often, defense contractors must surrender part of their profits
if production costs are lower than those anticipated in their
contracts.
   Hughes has built more than 400,000 of the TOW missiles. They are
tube-launched, optically tracked, wire-guided missiles, which are
designed to attack armored vehicles.
   Earlier this month, it was disclosed that another federal grand
jury is investigating whether Hughes consultants in South America
diverted some of their fees to a customer in connection with
satellite sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
