<DOCNO> AP880528-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 1836EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     05-28 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writers and Producers Off for Memorial Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both sides in the 12-week-old scriptwriters
strike took a break for the Memorial Day holiday Saturday with no
hint that the signing of contracts by dozens of independent
producers would hasten an agreement.
   Formal negotiations were scheduled to resume Tuesday between the
striking Writers Guild of America and the Alliance of Motion
Picture and Television Producers, under a federal mediator.
   By Friday, 73 companies had signed independent contracts with
the union, including the makers of such popular television shows as
``The Cosby Show,'' ``ALF,'' ``The Tonight Show Starring Johnny
Carson'' and ``Highway to Heaven.''
   The producer of ``Late Night With David Letterman'' agreed to a
contract but had not yet signed, Cheryl Rhoden, spokeswoman for the
9,000-member union, said Saturday.
   The contracts, ratified by guild members Thursday, will put 200
to 400 writers back to work, according to union estimates.
   The three-year contracts grant the writers' key demand:
retention of the present formula for the residual payments that
writers get for syndication of one-hour television shows.
   Union officials claimed the independent contracts split
management ranks, but Alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg said no
major company has settled with the writers.
   Many of those who did settle were one-person writer-producer
companies, including some that produce TV shows that have been
canceled, such as the Smothers Brothers' new comedy show, he said.
   ``Highway to Heaven'' star Michael Landon said he was glad
workers at his Michael Landon Productions would be back on the job.
``They have all been innocent victims and now they can all get back
to work,'' he said.
</TEXT>
