<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0624 05-28 0863</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0624,0890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Activists Drive In West Bank; Arabs Stone Army Post; Torture
Reported</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES, with more detail on reports of torture, EDITS
throughout to tighten and trim. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two convoys of Israeli peace activists drove
through the West Bank on Saturday to protest government policy in
the occupied territories, and Arabs in a Gaza Strip refugee camp
stoned the army headquarters.
   Three firebombs were hurled at an Arab's house Saturday in the
West Bank town of Ramallah and he opened fire, apparently wounding
one attacker, Israel radio reported. The army had no comment, but
Arab reports said the Palestinian was suspected of collaborating
with Israeli authorities.
   The army said it will launch a new probe into allegations by
some residents of Arura, also on the West Bank, that Israeli troops
tortured people when they raided the village earlier this month.
   A senior military official said the army was scheduled to reopen
secondary schools in the West Bank on Sunday, affecting about
70,000 Palestinian students. Kindergartens and elementary schools
were opened Monday last week after being closed nearly four months.
   Thousands of activists of the left-wing Peace Now movement drove
through the West Bank in two convoys of about 400 vehicles each.
They approached Nablus, the largest town, and later staged a
symbolic withdrawal from the occupied territory.
   Some Jewish settlers who encountered the convoys shouted insults
and several Arabs waved in support.
   Participants also held a rally south of Nablus during which
speakers criticized Jewish settlers in the occupied lands and
Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, whom they blamed for army tactics
of shooting and beating.
   They also urged Arabs to abandon violence and begin peace
negotiations with Israel, the state radio said.
   In Gaza's Jabaliya refugee camp, home to 53,000 Palestinians,
young Arabs threw stones and bottles at the army headquarters and
soldiers responded with tear gas grenades and rubber bullets, said
an Arab journalist speaking on condition of anonymity. No injuries
were reported.
   Several Palestinians were ordered to park their vehicles in
front of the army headquarters to prevent more attacks, he said.
   In the Shati refugee camp, the army ordered a curfew requiring
people to stay at home, and a commercial strike paralyzed Gaza
City. Young Palestinians stoned stoned cars and set tires ablaze.
   The protests occurred the day after a 3-year-old Palestinian
girl died in Gaza City. Relatives said she died of tear gas
inhalation after Israeli soldiers threw tear gas grenades, but
hospital officials said the army confirmed the death without giving
a cause.
   At least 198 Arabs have been killed since violence began Dec. 8
among the 1.5 million Palestinians of the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
war. An Israeli soldier and a Jewish settler also have been slain.
   Some residents of Arura complained to authorities about being
stoned, beaten and burned with cigarettes when troops raided the
village north of Ramallah on May 18.
   Villagers told Associated Press reporter Karin Laub earlier this
week that the raid on Arura, which its 2,000 residents have
declared ``liberated,'' started at 5 a.m. with 40 to 50 army
vehicles, two helicopters and a gravel-firing device.
   Mohammed Awad, 23, who had a swollen ankle, handcuffs marks on
his wrists and a blue mark on his right eye, said he was captured
by Israeli troops and ordered to sit in a hilltop stone pit.
   He said Hassan Salah, 22, and Mohammed Zeid, 29, were forced to
sit in similar six-foot-deep pits nearby.
   ``There were about 20 to 25 soldiers who threw stones at me and
the others,'' Awad said. ``It went on for two hours.''
   Awad said he was then taken with 12 other detainees to Ramallah
prison, and on the way soldiers threw burning cigarettes on them.
He said troops extinquished cigarettes on Bilal Mahmoud, 19.
   Daoud Suleiman Farradni, a Ramallah Hospital doctor who lives in
the village, said he examined Mahmoud after the event and found
eight to ten cigarette burns on his chest and ankles.
   On Awad, the doctor said:
   ``His face was swollen and covered with bruises. There were also
bruises and swelling on his waist and legs, either from stones or
clubs.''
   Earlier this week, the military command said ``an initial
investigation was made at the site and no evidence was found to
support the allegations.'' On Saturday, the army said it will
launch another probe.
   A senior official at the military administration said the army
was scheduled to open secondary schools, which cover grades 6-9, on
Sunday and high schools will open June 6.
   At the height of the rebellion in February, the military
government closed 1,200 schools in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
shutting out more than 300,000 students. Schools in Gaza have
operated on-and-off since.
   Schools had been major centers of protest in the first two
months of the uprising.
   Underground leaders of the 6-month-old Palestinian rebellion
issued a new leaflet calling for a general strike Monday and a
strike June 3-6 to protest the expected visit of U.S. Secretary of
State George P. Shultz.
</TEXT>
