<2ND_LINE>AM-Fawn Hall-Contras, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0615,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fawn Hall Gives Deposition in Contra Lawsuit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``The institute ...'' to CORRECT
spelling of Avirgan on second reference.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fawn Hall fended off a lawyer's questions
for two hours Saturday as part of a lawsuit in which a liberal
policy group has charged that several Iran-Contra figures were
involved in drug dealing.
   In a testy session, the former secretary to fired National
Security Council aide Oliver North delivered a deposition in which
she denied knowing several people involved in the suit. She was
accompanied by her lawyer, Plato Cacheris.
   Ms. Hall, who is not a defendant in the case, also denied
knowing about or said she had forgotten details of several meetings
and documents on which she was questioned.
   At one point, when lawyer Philip Hirschkop asked her about notes
North took after meetings, she snapped, ``I don't sit around and
watch my boss.''
   The session, held in Hirschkop's office in a suburb of
Washington, D.C., was open to the public.
   The civil lawsuit was filed two years ago by the Christic
Institute, which is based in Washington, D.C.
   The institute is representing two American journalists _ Martha
Honey and Tony Avirgan _ who are seeking $22 million for injuries
Avirgan suffered when a bomb exploded at a May 1986 news conference
held in Nicaragua by former Contra leader Eden Pastora. Three
reporters were killed in the blast.
   The suit accuses 29 defendants of a series of conspiracies,
including plans to provide weapons to the Contra rebels in
Nicaragua, smuggle cocaine into the United States to finance Contra
operations, and assassinate a U.S. ambassador in Costa Rica to
collect a bounty.
   The defendants include Richard V. Secord and Albert Hakim,
businessmen who have also face criminal charges of theft and
conspiracy in the Iran-Contra affair.
   Thomas Green, attorney for Secord and Hakim, attended the
deposition.
   The trial in the Christic suit is scheduled to begin June 26 in
Miami.
</TEXT>
