<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MassNationalGuard     05-28 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mass National Guard,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Despite Dukakis' Objections, Mass. Troops Head to Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the objections of Gov. Michael S. Dukakis,
13 Massachusetts National Guard public affairs specialists left
early Saturday for two weeks of training in Panama and Honduras.
   Dukakis, the frontrunner for the Democratic presidential
nomination, held a news conference at the Statehouse after the
group's departure but did not comment on it.
   Dukakis opposes the Reagan administration's deployment of
National Guard troops in Central America on constitutional grounds
and has appealed a U.S. District Court ruling on May 6 that upheld
the assignment.
   The governor did not seek to block the departure pending a
resolution of the appeal because he could not prove the detachment
would suffer irreparable harm, but his press aide said Dukakis
would continue to contest the issue.
   ``We feel there's an important constitutional issue involved
concerning the 200 years of responsibility which states and
governors have had over the peacetime training of their militia
forces,'' James Dorsey, the press secretary, said Friday.
   The detachment, which consists of writers and photographers for
the Massachusetts Guard's quarterly newsletter, will observe U.S.
forces in the field and prepare accounts of their actions.
   ``It's important training for the unit. It will be germane to
their overall mobilization training that they have this
experience,'' said Lt. Col. Stuart Taubert, director of press
relations for Adjutant General Wayne Wagner of the Massachusetts
National Guard.
   Major Warren Pierce, 39, of Duxbury, commander of the 65th
Public Affairs Detachment, said last week he had no reservations
about the assignment.
   ``We're looking forward to it,'' he said.
   In January, when the state's request to be excused from the
training mission was denied by the Pentagon, Dukakis and state
Attorney General James Shannon filed suit charging that the orders
violated the constitutional provision that left the training of the
``militia'' in the hands of the states.
   A similar suit filed by Minnesota Gov. Rudy Perpich was rejected
by another federal court and is also on appeal.
</TEXT>
