<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Protest     05-28 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Protest,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Party Causes Traffic Jams To Protest Election Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHIHUAHUA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of opposition party supporters
tied up traffic on several highways in northern Mexico on Saturday
to protest a mayoral election they say was rigged.
   About 150 protesters used cars to form a bottleneck for two
hours at the four-lane highway from Chihuahua to the border city of
Juarez. Tie-ups also were reported in Monterrey, Monclova and
several other northern Mexican cities.
   ``We're not trying to take your time. This is an act of peaceful
resistance,'' a protester in Chihuahua told waiting motorists by
loudspeaker. Motorists had to wait several minutes to pass.
   The demonstrations were mounted to protest Friday's announcement
that the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party won a special
mayoral election in Monclova in neighboring Coahuila state, 200
miles south of the Texas border at El Paso.
   The Coahuila legislature said governing party candidate Benigno
Franco Colorado defeated Carlos Paez Falcon of the opposition
National Action Party by 233 votes in Monclova's May 8 special
election.
   Franco was sworn in Saturday morning under tight security, but
no incidents were reported.
   The opposition party insists its candidate won by 448 votes and
that it has the precinct voting tallies to prove the results were
rigged.
   ``This is just the first in a series of actions we're planning
to support the people of Monclova,'' said Guillermo Prieto,
National Action president in Chihuahua state.
   In Monclova, Paez Falcon said about 1,000 supporters tied up
traffic in a two-hour demonstration on two highways. He said
protesters stopped cars briefly to distribute leaflets.
   The governing party won the gubernatorial race and 37 of the 38
mayoralties at stake in regular elections held last Oct. 25.
   But the state legislature annulled the Monclova elections,
citing voting irregularities and violence and called for special
elections.
   For nearly a decade, the two political parties have battled to
control Monclova, a major steel-producing city of 300,000 people.
   Its most recent administration was controlled by a bilateral
commission headed by the PRI and appointed after neither party
could prove it won the 1984 mayoral race.
</TEXT>
