<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 2032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Pool     05-28 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Pool,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Warships Makes Debut In Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD USS VINCENNES IN THE PERSIAN GULF (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most
powerful U.S. warship ever seen in the Persian Gulf passed through
the Strait of Hormuz Saturday on its first mission in the war-torn
waterway.
   The guided missile cruiser USS Vincennes, with 385 officers and
crewmen aboard, entered the gulf to begin the first deployment in
the region by any of the navy's 10 Aegis cruisers.
   The 9,400-ton warship, commissioned in 1985 and equipped with
sophisticated radar and weapons systems, is the fourth U.S. Navy
warship named for the Indiana town where a decisive Revolutionary
War battle was fought.
   The level of tension ran fairly high during the ship's nighttime
run up the narrow strait. It passed about four miles from a
Panamanian-flag tanker, still on fire 20 hours after being attacked
by Iranian speedboats.
   Salvage tugboats were pouring water on the ship, which was
listing and appeared to have suffered severe fire damage to its
superstructure.
   The Vincennes crew also saw flames leaping high in the sky from
a burning structure on the Iranian side of the strait. It was not
certain whether it may have been Larak Island, an Iranian offshore
oil terminal devastated by Iraqi warplanes in a raid two weeks ago.
   The fast-moving warship was challenged by one of the Omani navy
boats that regularly patrol the straits to identify itself, and the
Vincennes, observing the standard Gulf protocol, said that it was
``an American warship, hull number 49.''
   Later, as it passed the Iran-held island of Abu Musa in the
southern gulf, the cruiser exchanged greetings with the missile
frigate Jack Williams, one of five U.S. ships scheduled to depart
the gulf in a few more days.
   Capt. Will C. Rogers III, skipper of the Vincennes, says the
ship is preparing for its gulf duty with help from one of the
strongest support networks for any ship in the U.S. Navy.
   Rogers said the Indiana town keeps a close eye on its namesake.
It hosts a civic blowout every August, a Christmas project in which
students at Vincennes University send gifts to every man aboard and
a two-year Vincennes University scholarship that goes annually to
the cruiser's ``sailor of the year.''
   `I've been on a lot of ships, and I've never seen anything like
it.'' Rogers said.
   Rogers said the active Vincennes support group began with three
veterans of the World War II-era cruiser by that name. It now has
more than 650 members, including Rogers and about 70 others of the
current ship's crew.
   The USS Vincennes Association has held annual reunions for the
past 13 years, with the Indiana town hosting parades and a feast
that last year featured 600 pounds of fresh catfish.
   Rogers, who attended the 1987 festival, said, ``I don't think
I've ever been made to feel so welcome or have been so royally
treated as in those four days.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
