<HEAD>Emir Appeals to Superpower Leaders On Palestinians</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a 46-nation Islamic organization on
Saturday appealed to President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev to look for a solution to the Palestinian situation
during their summit in Moscow.
   ``What is the difference between the Afghan mujahedeen and
Palestinian mujahedeen?'' asked the emir of Kuwait, Sheik Jaber
Ahmed Sabah, in a letter sent to the superpower leaders.
   ``Both peoples have an inalienable and historical right to their
country,'' said the emir, who sent the letter as chairman of the
Organization of Islamic Conference, which groups all Islamic
nations.
   Afghan guerrillas known as the mujahedeen, or ``holy warriors,''
are fighting the Soviet-backed government in Kabul.
   The emir praised the withdrawal of Soviets forces from
Afghanistan. He urged Reagan and Gorbachev to try to resolve the
Middle East problem, the Iran-Iraq war and the Lebanon crisis at
the summit.
   ``The Palestinian uprising should figure prominently in your
talks because what the Palestinians are currently suffering on the
land of their ancestors is but a form of flagrant aggression on
human rights and peace,'' he said.
   He referred to the Palestinian uprising since Dec. 8 against
Israeli rule in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, captured by
the Jewish state in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war. At least 198
Palestinians and two Israelis have been killed in clashes.
