<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Italy-Strikes,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airport Ground Personnel Reach Tentative Agreement On Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unions representing airport ground workers reached a
tentative agreement Saturday with Alitalia and airport officials on
a new contract that may end months of disruptive wildcat strikes.
   The accord, which must be approved Monday by the country's main
trade union federation, was defined as ``conclusive and
unmodifiable'' by the unions, Rome's airport association and
Alitalia, Italy's state-run airline.
   Union officials said the pact provides improvements over the
accord signed by unions in March but rejected by the rank-and-file
in a referendum April 1.
   Under the accord, ground workers would receive an annual pay
increase of about $2,850 by July 1990, the news agency AGI
reported. The agency said weekly working hours would be reduced
from 41{ to 37{ over five years.
   For months, ground workers have staged temporary strikes at
Italian airports.
</TEXT>
