<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Elections     05-28 0136</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Elections,0141</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>7 Million To Vote In Local Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italians were to elect members of three provincial
councils and 1,200 town councils Sunday and Monday in the first
elections since Premier Ciriaco De Mita and his five-party
coalition formed a government last month.
   More than one-fifth of the Italian electorate _ 7 million voters
_ are eligible to choose the councils in towns and Pavia, Ravenna
and Viterbo provinces.
   Political commentators say the elections will focus on local
issues and are not expected to affect the balance of power in
national politics.
   But the results will give an indication of the political climate
after De Mita, leader of the conservative Christian Democrats,
formed Italy's 48th postwar government.
   The other partners in the coalition are the Socialists, the
Social Democrats, Republicans and Liberals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
