<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 2054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ToxicShip     05-28 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toxic Ship,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Ship Of Poison' To Sail To Genoa To Unload Toxic Cargo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARRARA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Syrian freighter carrying 2,000 tons of
toxic chemical waste will sail Sunday to Genoa to unload cargo that
first left this port for disposal 15 months ago, officials said.
   Giuseppe Francese, the port commissioner in Genoa, made the
decision to allow the Zanoobia, known in Italy as the ``ship of
poison,'' to unload in Genoa. Two people have died after possible
contamination by its waste after stops in Djibouti, Venezuela,
Syria and Greece.
   Francese said Genoa, 60 miles northwest of Carrara, is the only
Italian port that can safely unload and incinerate the 12,000 drums
of unidentified chemical waste from Italian chemical companies.
   The regional Ministry of Civil Protection approved the unloading
but said the ship must be moored in an isolated spot and
precautions must be taken to prevent fires or toxic fumes.
   Lawyers for the ship owner, Tabalo Shipping, say two people _ a
boy in Venezuela and a crewman during the voyage to Italy _ have
died after possible contamination by the waste.
   One of the attorneys, Francesco Rizzuto, said Italian
authorities are investigating.
   Three crewmen are hospitalized in nearby Massa suffering from
headaches, burning eyes, blisters, rashes or respiratory problems
attributed to the wastes.
   The ship has been anchored outside the Tuscan port of Carrara
since April 26.
   Rizzuto said a group of Italian shipping companies paid the
Milan-based company Jelly Wax to dispose of the waste. He said the
company instead shipped the waste out of the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
