<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CubanPrisoner 1stLd-Writethru a0658 05-28 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuban Prisoner, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prisoner Returned to U.S. Via Jackson Is Charged With Kidnapping</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 grafs after 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``Young was ...''
to UPDATE with Jackson comment.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LAKE PARK, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of 48 prisoners released by Cuban
President Fidel Castro when Jesse Jackson visited Cuba in 1984 has
been charged with kidnapping and aggravated battery, police said.
   Robert Samuel Young, 39, was arrested at 6:30 p.m. Friday, after
more than a dozen Palm Beach County sheriff's deputies and police
circled a house where he and his girlfriend, Kathleen Kunzig, were
holed up, said sheriff's Lt. Donald Ganzel.
   They surrendered a few minutes later, said sheriff's detective
Charles Comfort.
   Young was being held without bond Saturday in the Palm Beach
County Jail on warrants charging kidnapping and aggravated battery,
a jail spokeswoman said.
   Ms. Kunzig, 33, also was being held without bond on a Broward
County warrant charging armed kidnapping, according to a
spokeswoman at the Palm Beach County Stockade.
   Young was one of 22 Americans freed from Cuba prisons after
Jackson, then as now a presidential candidate, made a humanitarian
mission to Cuba. Twenty-six Cubans were also freed. Young had been
jailed in Havana for three years on a drug smuggling charge, The
Miami Herald reported Saturday.
   Jackson, campaigning Saturday in New Jersey, was asked about
Young's arrest and replied: ``I don't know anything about that. I
haven't had any contact with them since I got them out.''
   The kidnapping charges stem from last August when a man was
ambushed after he repossessed a sailboat when Young defaulted on a
$15,000 loan, said Fort Lauderdale police Detective Steve
Robitaille.
   The ambush was allegedly carried out by Young, Ms. Kunzig and
two other men. Young shot the man twice and tortured him for two
hours until he revealed where a repossessed boat was docked,
Robitaille said.
   Fort Lauderdale police arrested Young in September, but he fled
several weeks later after posting $125,000 bond, the detective said.
   ``Bobby is a bad guy,'' said Robitaille, who has been hunting
for him since he disappeared last fall. ``He's definitely somebody
to be afraid of.''
   Young also is a suspect in the 1984 murder of John Panzavecchia
of Davie, said Miami homicide detectives Nelson Andreu and Jon
Spear. Panzavecchia's widow, Candy Panzavecchia, told police Young
and Ms. Kunzig were with her husband when he was killed.
   Young has not been charged in that shooting, police said.
   Castro has often been accused of releasing violent prisoners to
the United States on ostensibly humanitarian grounds.
</TEXT>
