<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0651 05-28 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0651,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Promotes Himself To ``The General'' In Drug War</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 1 graf with endorsement from black trade unionists.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential hopeful Jesse
Jackson on Saturday declared himself ``the general'' of the war on
drugs, while saying rival Michael Dukakis was just a captain and
Republican George Bush only a lieutenant.
   ``Bush thinks crack is sound. He doesn't know crack is a drug,''
Jackson said.
   Jackson told an enthusiastic crowd at a Hispanic Memorial Day
weekend picnic, Dukakis and Republican nominee-apparent Bush are
newcomers to the drug fight.
   ``Bush is lieutenant, Dukakis is a captain, but I'm the general
in this war on drugs,'' he declared.
   Jackson made light of the vice president's recent trip to an
alleged ``crack house'' in Los Angeles. Bush was accompanied by his
security detail and L.A. police officials.
   Jackson said Bush went on the excursion dressed in a
``bulletproof vest ... football pads ... high-button shoes.''
   Earlier, at an Atlantic City housing projet, Jackson blasted
Bush and the Reagan administration for what he called their
faltering anti-drug efforts.
   Jackson, campaigning in anticipation of New Jersey's June 7
primary, again attacked the administration's failed attempt to
negotiate an agreement with Panamanian strongman Manuel Noriega.
   Secretary of State George Shultz said earlier this week that
Noriega had abruptly changed his mind on an agreement to leave
Panama in return for the United States dropping its drug-dealing
indictment against him.
   ``Silence for sanctuary is sleeze. And that's a bad deal,''
Jackson said.
   He exhorted the housing project residents to join him in forcing
out drug pushers. Police said the area, within sight of streamlined
casino towers, is beset with drugs and gang violence
   ``There is no place in this housing project for dope pushers. I
say drive them out,'' Jackson said to cheers.
   He said blacks face a threat from drug dealers like they once
faced from the Ku Klux Klan.
   ``At least the Klansmen wore hoods. Those who push dope don't
wear hoods, they are hoods,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, the Jackson campaign got a boost Saturday from the
nation's largest black labor organization. The Coalition of Black
Trade Unionists approved a resolution endorsing Jackson at its
annual convention in Washington.
</TEXT>
