<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 2150EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Soviet-Reunion     05-28 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Reunion,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Woman Told Soviet Husband Will Be Allowed To Emigrate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Florida neurologist whose Soviet husband has been
seeking permission to leave the Soviet Union for eight years said
Saturday she has received word that her husband will be allowed to
emigrate.
   Pyotr Pakenas has had 17 requests to emigrate denied since 1980,
when his wife, Dr. Galina Vileshina, 51, and two children left the
Soviet Union.
   Ms. Vileshina, who has waged a well-publicized campaign to
reunite her family, said she received notice from the State
Department on Saturday that Pakenas would be allowed to leave the
Soviet Union.
   ``So far I don't understand. To be honest I am really shocked,
and I can't believe it has really happened,'' she said Saturday
night in a telephone interview from her daughter's house in North
Palm Beach. ``Of course I'm superstitious. I worry about the plane,
the trip.''
   She said she believed the timing of the decision was tied to
President Reagan's Moscow summit meeting with Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev, which starts Sunday.
   ``Of course, it's because of the summit and because of the
pressure of the American government,'' said Ms. Vileshina, who met
with Secretary of State George P. Shultz on Monday in Washington
about her husband's situation.
   ``I was waiting eight years for this happy moment in my life. I
started to cry, my body was shaking I was so happy,'' Ms. Vileshina
said.
   The family has stayed close through daily letters and weekly
telephone calls, and Ms. Vileshina visited with her husband in
Moscow last October.
   ``They said that we have very good news; your case has been
resolved,'' Pakenas' 29-year-old daughter, Laura Abovich, said of
the call from the State Department. Her 7-year-old son Eric has
never met his grandfather.
   Pakenas, 54, has received an invitation to meet with Reagan on
Monday as part of a small group of Soviet refuseniks, including
some so-called divided spouses, Mrs. Abovich said.
   She said the family called Pakenas after receiving the news, and
``he'll try to get out as soon as possible.''
   Asked when he might arrive, Mrs. Abovich said, ``We just can
judge from other people's cases, anywhere from two weeks to up to
six weeks. It really depends on the paperwork.''
   ``The last six months, especially after this last summit in
December,'' were the most difficult, Mrs. Abovich said. ``Waiting
every day, every day.''
   Ms. Vileshina said during her visit with her husband last year
that he had developed heart trouble and high blood pressure and
needed better medical treatment than he could get in the Soviet
Union.
   News of the breakthrough was hailed by Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla.,
who had been one of the family's supporters.
   ``She heard very good news today, but the real celebration will
occur when her husband joins his family on free soil,'' Graham
said. ``Our goal has been to reunite a family that suffered
separation long enough.''
</TEXT>
