<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 2156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SteroidDefense     05-28 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steroid Defense,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Lawyer: Steroid Addiction Made Client Violent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note 3rd graf may be offensive to some readers.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Addiction to anabolic steroids
turned a mild-mannered man into a ``seething volcano'' of violence,
maintains the defense laywer for a body-builder accused of killing
a hitchhiker.
   Horace Williams, 23, is charged with first-degree murder in the
September 1986 beating death of Michael Shane Patterson in Boca
Raton. The trial, being taped by a California television production
company for a series called ``On Trial,'' opened here Friday.
   Patterson's battered, naked body was found suspended between two
poles in a field, with his hands tied to one pole and his feet to
the other. He died from severe internal injuries that were
aggravated by the way he had been tied up, says a Palm Beach County
Medical Examiner's report.
   In his opening statement Friday, defense lawyer Richard Lubin
said he will fashion an insanity defense around expert testimony
that an 18-month regimen of almost daily steroid treatments caused
Williams' mental health to deteriorate ``without him even knowing
about it.''
   Anabolic steroids _ synthetic versions of the male hormone
testosterone _ are used by some athletes and weightlifters to
stimulate the production of proteins that increase muscle size and
strength.
   The drugs, which are available legally only by prescription,
also are blamed for making users more aggressive.
   
   The steroids made Williams ``a powder keg'' whose ``delusions
and mixed-up perception'' made it impossible for him to know that
the beating he gave Patterson caused his death, Lubin said.
   Assistant State Attorney Charles Burton called Patterson's death
a ``gruesome, brutal murder'' in which Williams and his friend,
William Whitmore, 21, tortured their victim for more than 30
minutes before leaving him for dead.
   Whitmore pleaded guilty to second-degree murder earlier this
month in exchange for a 40-year prison sentence.
   On the night Patterson was killed, Whitmore introduced his
friend, Edward Danielson, to Williams. Danielson, who is not
charged in the killing, testified Friday that the three men left
his house in search of a party.
   Later, they picked up Patterson hitchhiking, gave him a beer and
took him to a field, Danielson said. There, Williams demanded
money, and when Patterson said he had no cash, Williams told him to
strip, Danielson testified.
   Williams shredded Patterson's pants, and then Whitmore and
Williams began punching the man, he said.
   ``(Patterson) stood up and tried to run, but Horace grabbed him
from behind and stopped him,'' said Danielson, a Navy airman
stationed in Massachusetts.
   ``(Patterson) grabbed a board and tried to hit Horace, and then
he took the board and hit (Patterson) on top of the head,'' he
testified, adding that the victim pleaded for his life throughout
the ordeal.
   Police have alleged that Williams and Whitmore also beat
Patterson with a pipe, cut hair from his head and underarms, and
rammed his body with a car before tying him up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
