<HEAD>Kansas Man, Panhandle Woman Win Annual Competition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEAVER, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Kansas man successfully defended his
title Saturday in the 19th World Championship Cow Chip Throwing
Contest but strong winds derailed the defending woman's champion.
   Roy Kygar of Kismet, Kan., won the men's title with a fling of
151 feet, 2 inches.
   Winds that gusted over 30 mph weren't as kind to five-time
defending woman's champion Kay Hankins of Prairie Du Sac, Wis.,
blowing both of her chips out of bounds.
   That opened the door for Catherine Westenhaver of Forgan, 7
miles north of here, who won with a toss of 83 feet.
   The contest capped a week of festivities in this small Panhandle
town of about 6,800. The contest's raw material _ dried, flattened
chunks of cow dung _ was hauled in from local pastures.
   Trophies and jackets also were presented to winners in
children's and VIP divisions.
