<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rightist Party Nominates Presidential Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance nominated businessman Alfredo Cristiani on
Saturday as its candidate for the March 1989 presidential election.
   Cristiani, 42, president of the party known by its Spanish
acronym Arena, was unopposed for the nomination.
   Party leaders said internal divisions have split the governing
Christian Democrats and would make Cristiani El Salvador's next
president.
   Arena founder Roberto d'Aubuisson, who sponsored the nomination,
called Cristiani ``my brother'' and ``the man who will take us to
victory. The armed forces respect him.,'' d'Aubuisson told party
supporters at the nominating convention.
   In his acceptance speech, Cristiani accused the government of
corruption and attacked the leftist Faribundo Marti National
Liberation Front, which has waged an 8-year-old guerrilla war
against the U.S.-supported government.
   ``The people already have turned their backs to the
(guerrillas),'' said Cristiana.
   Arena won at least 30 of the 60 seats in the National Assembly
in elections held March 20. The party has asked the Supreme Court
to reverse the awarding of another seat to the Christian Democrats.
   The governing party chose Julio Adolfo Rey Prendes as its
candidate last month in a bitter nominating convention that was
boycotted by Fidel Chavez Mena, his chief rival, and President Jose
Napoleon Duarte, the Christian Democrats' honorary chairman.
   Under law, Duarte, elected in 1984, cannot run for a second
five-year term.
   In an interview with The Associated Press in April, Cristiani
said that if Arena won the presidency, Washington's Salvador policy
would have to change drastically.
   ``Relations will have to be based on mutual respect. No more
coming down here and saying, `Here's so many millions of dollars
and this is what you have to do,''' he said.
   Cristiani said the State Department and U.S. Embassy have waged
a consistent campaign against Arena, founded in 1981.
   ``We have always felt under tremendous attack from the
government of the United States,'' he said, though he noted
conservative Salvadorans maintain an abiding affinity for the
United States.
   ``The U.S. is our natural ally,'' he said in the interview.
