<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IndictedChairman     05-28 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indicted Chairman,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Under Indictment Named County Democratic Chairman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to CORRECT cycle designator.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state senator, under indictment on a
charge that he accepted a bribe while serving as a county
commissioner, has been named chairman of the Mingo County
Democratic Party.
   Sen. Truman Chafin is the fifth consecutive Mingo County
Democratic chairman to face criminal charges.
   He faces a state bribery charge in a scheme to sell the
sheriff's job from Johnie Owens to Charles ``Eddie'' Hilbert for
$100,000. Owens, a former county Democratic chairman, and Hilbert
have pleaded guilty to charges in connection with the scheme.
   Chafin, accused of accepting a bribe to stay away from the
commission meeting which approved the transfer of the job from
Owens to Hilbert, has pleaded innocent and denies any involvement
in the alleged scheme.
   The county Democratic Executive Committee voted 7-6 Thursday to
name Chafin county chairman.
   The previous chairman, E. Donald Evans, resigned at the request
of the U.S. attorney's office after being indicted a month ago on a
conspiracy to commit vote fraud charge.
   His predecessor was Owens, who is serving a 14-year federal
prison sentence.
   Owens' predecessor as chairman was Stewart Justice, who was
acquitted on a state bribery charge last year. Justice's
predecessor, Noah Floyd, was acquitted on federal conspiracy
charges in the early 1970s.
   The politically powerful county chairmanship had been vacant for
a month since Evans resigned. Local politicians say they can never
remember the post being vacant for so long.
   Mingo, a poverty-stricken coal-mining county, has borne a
reputation for corruption for years. In 1986, the fire chief of
Kermit was convicted of running a ``drug carry-out'' operation next
door to the town police department.
   In elections for county office on May 11, the voters rejected
three of five candidates under criminal indictment.
</TEXT>
