<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia-EEC     05-28 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-EEC,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethopia Will Allow EEC To Monitor Relief Operations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopia will allow the European
Economic Community to monitor drought relief operations in the
war-torn north following an EEC threat to cut off food shipments,
an European official said Saturday.
   EEC delegate Benno Haffner told reporters he received assurances
from officials of the Marxist government Friday night that he can
visit the northern provinces this week.
   The assurances follow an EEC letter to the government's chief
relief official, Berhanu Jembere, expressing ``deep concern and
regret'' over the situation and threatening to cut off further food
shipments.
   The EEC is Ethiopia's biggest food donor, followed by the United
States and the Soviet Union.
   The government has requested emergency aid to help feed 7
million people threatened with starvation nationwide following
severe crop failures.
   Haffner said the letter followed the government's failure to
fulfill a contract permitting a representative of the European
community to visit regions where EEC food is distributed.
   The EEC is giving 234,000 tons of emergency food to Ethiopia, 75
percent of which is going to the provinces of Eritrea and Tigre,
where an estimated 3.2 million drought victims live.
   Haffner said the government has not allowed an EEC delegate to
visit the war-torn regions since April 6, when Ethiopia expelled
foreign aid workers from the north following a string of rebel
victories which a government withdrawal.
   Insurgents have been fighting the government for 14 years in
Tigre and for 27 years in Eritrea.
   Marxist Ethiopia will not allow relief officials to operate
beyond the shrunken areas still under its control. Western relief
officials estimate 2 million people in Eritrea and Tigre are
outside government-controlled areas and are in danger of starving
to death.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
