<HEAD>Thailand Calls For Pressure, Repatriation of Vietnamese</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   CHA-AM, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand on Saturday urged international
pressure on Hanoi and the repatriation of Vietnamese fleeing their
country who are determined to be migrants rather than refugees.
   Participants at a conference on Vietnamese ``boat people'' also
called for more resettlement of refugees by third countries and an
expanded Orderly Departure Program from Vietnam to alleviate what
they said was the ``gravest Indochinese refugee crisis since 1979.''
   ``Pressure must be exerted by all concerned on Vietnam to
recognize the humanitarian consequences of the (refugee) outflow
and the negative image created for Vietnam,'' a senior Thai Foreign
Ministry official, Pracha Guna-kasem, said at the conclusion of a
four-day meeting.
   The conference, sponsored by the Ford Foundation, brought
together officials from the six countries of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations, as well as Hong Kong, the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees and observers from Japan, Sweden, United
States, Australia and New Zealand.
   The group's recommendations are to be submitted at a ASEAN-Hong
Kong meeting in Bangkok this week.
   The U.N. refugee commission said that it was handling about
40,000 Vietnamese boat people in Asia as of March 31 this year, up
from 32,000 the same period two years ago.
   The largest numbers are found in Thailand, Malaysia, Hong Kong,
the Philippines and Indonesia.
