<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Nome-Provideniya     05-28 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nome-Provideniya,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Approve `Friendship Flight' Between U.S.-U.S.S.R.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed flight from Nome to the
Siberian town of Provideniya won Soviet clearance on Saturday, but
it came as such a surprise that the ``Friendship Flight'' dreamed
2{ years ago must be delayed.
   Soviet officials told Gov. Steve Cowper the 240-mile flight can
take place on Tuesday, the day Alaska's organizers of the trip
proposed months ago.
   Alaska Airlines has to postpone the flight, however, to ensure
Provideniya's runway can withstand a jet filled with politicians,
business leaders, the press and Eskimo people seeking reunions with
Siberian kin.
   ``We were aware of the fact that the Soviets normally give you
pretty short notice on decisions like this, so it was not a
surprise that they called four days before it was supposed to
happen,'' Cowper said.
   Approval of the trip clearly was tied to the Moscow summit talks
between President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev,
Cowper said. He said he hopes the trip can take place in June.
   Cowper said the clearance of a flight for Tuesday was
particularly surprising because he thought Soviet officials were
concerned the journey would draw some attention away from the
summit.
   Alaska Airlines hopes to send technical staff to Provideniya in
a twin-engine plane on Tuesday, airline spokesman Jim Johnson said.
Permission for the ``pre-flight'' was sought through diplomatic
channels on Saturday.
   ``They (the Soviets) gave us some information about the runway,
but we need to see first hand if it's suitable for a jet,'' Johnson
said.
   Nome businessman Jim Stimpfle has been pushing the trip for 2{
years. He said he used to stand on a Bering Sea beach and wonder
what was going across the water in the Soviet Union.
   People in Nome remember how he used to send balloons containing
gum and sewing needles over the ocean in hopes they would reach
people on Siberia's Chukotsk Peninsula.
   ``It's been a day that I think we will all remember, and
hopefully it will be the beginning of many good things between the
Soviet Union and the people of Alaska,'' Stimpfle said Saturday.
   Alaska Airlines wants to use a Boeing 737 for the 25-minute
flight from Nome to Provideniya and is hopes that with only about
70 passengers instead of the usual 111 and luggage, Provideniya's
rustic runway will handle the plane.
   Airline officials have been told the runway is between 1600 and
1800 meters and has a surface of gravel and sand, but they've also
heard it described as a ``dirt'' landing strip. They want to see it
for themselves, Johnson said.
   He said the flight can be arranged quickly once the runway
conditions are known. Plans call for a morning departure from Nome,
an early dinner in Provideniya and an evening flight back to Nome
across the Bering Sea.
   The trip has become one of the more attention-getting components
of Alaska's effort to establish ties and possibly eventual trade
with the Soviet Union.
   Several weeks ago, Gorbachev's chief spokesman, Gennadi
Gerasimov, spoke optimistically in Alaska about the prospects for
warmer relations between the neighbors.
   Passengers aboard the flight are expected to include Eskimos
separated from their kin for decades by the political chill between
the United States and the Soviet Union.
   Alaska Airlines is hoping the flight will be more than a media
event, and is interested in offering regular service to
Provideniya's peninsula.
</TEXT>
