<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MechamTrial     05-28 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham Trial,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Trial Jury Sworn In</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve jurors were sworn in Friday for
former Gov. Evan Mecham's criminal trial on charges of concealing a
$350,000 campaign loan.
   Mecham, 64, faces up to 22 years in prison if convicted of all
six felony counts of perjury, willful concealment and filing false
documents. Willard Mecham, who was his brother's 1986 campaign
treasurer, faces three similar counts and up to 9{ years in prison.
Both have denied any wrongdoing.
   Mecham did not attend Friday's session in Maricopa County
Superior Court. He was traveling to Altamont, Utah, to address
graduates at his former high school. Mecham's brother and
co-defendant, Willard Mecham, sat with his lawyer.
   Opening statements are scheduled for Thursday, one day after the
Arizona Supreme Court hears arguments on a defense request to
return the charges to the state grand jury for a new determination
of probable cause.
   Mecham, a Republican who took office in January 1987, was
removed from office April 4 when the state Senate convicted him of
two unrelated impeachment counts.
   The jurors include five Republicans and two Democrats.
   Nine said they had no opinion on whether Mecham should have been
recalled from office, while three said they opposed a recall. A
recall election had been scheduled for May but was abandoned after
Mecham's impeachment conviction.
   ``I think this is a jury that's capable of giving us a fair
trial,'' said the former governor's attorney, Michael Scott.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
