<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Marcos-Paintings     05-28 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos-Paintings,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paintings Wanted by Philippines Flown to U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen paintings taken from the Philippines by
Ferdinand Marcos were flown to the United States where they may be
used as evidence in an investigation into possible misuse of public
funds by Marcos, a lawyer said Friday.
   The paintings were shipped out Thursday. They included some that
are part of a lawsuit filed in the United States by the government
of President Cory Aquino in an attempt to recover property
purportedly taken by former President Marcos and his wife, Imelda,
when they fled Manila in 1986.
   Olivier Laude, one of the lawyers representing the United States
in the French legal proceedings, said the works were brought to
France for the Marcoses in 1986 aboard the plane of Saudi
businessman Adnan Khashoggi.
   The paintings were secretly stored in the French Riviera. Laude
said it was not clear exactly how many paintings were involved.
   Le Monde newspaper said Friday that about 30 paintings, among
them works by Spanish master El Greco and French romanticist
Francois Boucher, were involved.
   Laude declined to place a value on the works returned Thursday
or say to whom they were delivered, noting: ``There is a New York
grand jury investigating the Marcoses and the way they used public
funds given by the United States to the Philippines.''
</TEXT>
