<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 0547EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-RisingRight-Europe Adv06   05-28 1111</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rising Right-Europe, Adv 06,1141</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs June 6 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Le Pen's Success in France Fuels Hopes of European Extreme Right</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: A companion story is AM-Rising Right-Italy, b0458</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto
^By SYDNEY RUBIN</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The strong showing in the French presidential
elections of National Front leader Jean-Marie Le Pen has lent
encouragement to others in Western Europe who share his
nationalistic, anti-immigrant views.
   Le Pen's main campaign theme _ France for Frenchmen _ contended
that an influx of immigrants, mainly Arabs from North Africa, was
diluting French traditions and adding to the nation's economic and
social problems.
   He is said to be planning to take his message to other European
countries.
   After Le Pen won more than 14 percent of the vote in
presidential balloting April 24, extreme right wing parties in
Belgium, Italy, Greece and elsewhere expressed hope that his
success would be contagious. The National Front now holds 35 seats
in the 577-member French National Assembly.
   Chrysanthos Dimitriades, a member of the European Parliament and
of Greece's extreme right National Political Union, told The
Associated Press that Le Pen's gains ``improved our spirit, there
has been a positive change.''
   The Belgium National Front, a sister to the French party, ``got
hundreds of phone calls from people who wanted to join'' after the
April 24 vote, said party spokesman Daniel Feret.
   ``Basically we heard from people who share our ideas but thought
we were a marginal party. Le Pen changed that,'' he said.
   Le Pen's campaign subtly conveyed the message that dark-skinned
foreigners are invaders who undermine the French way of life and
take jobs. His speeches tapped a vague, mostly unarticulated
feeling that France is on the decline, its traditions in jeopardy
and its ``national identity'' threatened.
   He kept the immigration issue at the center of his campaign,
suggesting legal measures to encourage immigrants in France to move
elsewhere and limiting the number of immigrant children in schools.
He appealed to nationalistic sentiments and authoritarian values,
favoring restoration of the death penalty and the quarantining of
AIDS victims.
   Europe's extreme right parties share a common desire to convert
concern about immigration into votes, but they have yet to come
near getting the kind the success Le Pen's National Front received
in France, even though their countries face economic and social
problems similar to those of the French.
   Some of the parties have registered some successes but others
remain far out on the fringe, with little or no representation in
their respective parliaments and little chance right now of
influencing governments.
   In Greece, for example, Dimitriades' National Political Union
won just 0.6 percent of the vote in the last national elections, in
1985, and that represented a drop from the 2.3 percent it won in
the European Parliament vote a year earlier. While Dimitriades won
a seat in the European Parliament in Strasbourg, his party remains
out of Parliament at home.
   Belgium's National Front also has no representation in the
nation's 212-seat House of Representatives and is so far out on the
fringes that it does not figure in public-opinion polls.
   Le Pen's National Front holds 35 just seats in France's
577-member National Assembly, but he himself has been gaining over
the years _ from 0.74 percent of the vote in the 1974 presidential
election, 11 percent in the 1984 European Parliament balloting to
14.4 percent in April.
   Gianfranco Fini, secretary of the vaguely neo-fascist Italian
Social Movement, is optimistic about the outcome in France.
   He maintains immigrants pose a grave threat to all European
countries.
   Unemployment in Italy is 12.4 percent, and yet immigrants from
Africa and Asia come ashore at the rate of 50,000 a year. Although
90,000 foreigners were legally registered in October 1987,
unofficial estimates put the number of illegal immigrants at
800,000. Racial animosity has risen in Italy along with the
immigration.
   Fini's party won 5.9 percent of the vote in parliamentary
elections last June. It holds 35 seats in the 630-member Chamber of
Deputies, making it Italy's fourth largest party, but it does not
figure prominently in the shaping of Italian governments or
policies.
   Even so, foreign workers are an issue in Italy. The largest
daily newspaper, La Repubblica, published a survey in early May of
high school students that it said indicated ``open hostility''
toward immigrants.
   Seventy percent of those responding said they would favor a
partial or total closing of borders to foreigners who ``rob us of
work.''
   In France, an intellectual ``new right'' is providing a
theoretical framework for neo-fascism. So-called revisionist
historians are publishing works that re-examine the country under
Nazi occupation and question whether the extermination of 6 million
Jews during World War II actually occurred.
   Le Pen referred to the gassing of Jews in Nazi death camps as
``a detail of history.''
   Similarly in Italy, a spate of books and articles is reassessing
the Italy of dictator Benito Mussolini in the years before and
during World War II. A leading Mussolini historian has suggested
that ``laws forbidding the re-establishment of the Fascist Party
are anachronistic.''
   Le Pen visited Rome on May 8, taking his message to a cheering
crowd at an Italian Social Movement meeting. He plans similar trips
around Europe in the coming months, said his spokesman Alain Vizier.
   But Le Pen's presence already has been felt abroad.
   Mogens Glistrip, leader of the Denmark's anti-immigration
Progress Party, is frequently referred to in the press as the local
Le Pen.
   In Danish parliamentary elections in May, Glistrip's party took
16 of the legislature's 179 seats, up from 9. It was the second big
gain in a row for the party, which had increased its holdings from
6 in another election last September.
   Norway's Carl I. Hagen also is compared to Le Pen. He leads the
Norwegian branch of the Progress Party that won 12.2 percent of the
popular vote in local elections last fall. Recent opinion polls
give the party 15 to 23 percent, making it Norway's second largest
party after the governing Labor Party.
   Hagen advocates limiting immigration based on the availablity of
housing and jobs.
   Political analyst Ole Borre of Denmark's Aarhus University said
the swing to the right in Denmark and Norway is part ``of an
international trend.''
   Some observers contend Le Pen's success is unique, a product of
the two-tier French election process and the candidate's
personality.
   Greece's Dimitriades says groups like his pose no immediate
challenge to existing European democracies.
   ``There is a swing toward conservatism in Europe,'' Dimitriades
said, ``but it's too early to say if it is swinging into our
sphere.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon AMs June 6</NOTE>
