<1ST_LINE>a a BC-TickerTalk Adv30   05-28 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 30,0657</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday, May 30</NOTE>
<HEAD>Wall Street Watchword: `All News Is Bad News'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recent events on Wall Street have taken a lot of
the suspense out of the various periodic government reports on the
state of the economy.
   Followers of the stock market are familiar with the usual
routine: Investors set their sights on a forthcoming report
regarding something like the trade deficit and try to anticipate
what it will look like.
   If, when the number arrives, it is better than expected, stock
prices rally. If it falls short of expectations, the market falls.
   The exercise can get convoluted at times, on the theory that
what looks good for the current economy might actually be an
ominous portent for interest rates, inflation and the business
outlook at some point in the future.
   Lately, however, the game has been simplified. If the trade
deficit rises, stocks fall. If the trade deficit narrows, well,
stocks also fall.
   As Jack Lavery, research director at Merrill Lynch, put it
recently: ``Good news is bad news and bad news is bad news.''
   However perverse that may sound, long-time students of the stock
market say it is neither unprecedented nor illogical.
   The relationship between stocks and the economic news is often
tenuous, they say. If investors are sufficiently fearful, they may
well find an ostensibly positive development uninspiring.
   In fact, traders who want to lighten their stock holdings may
seize on ``good news'' as an opportune moment to sell.
   John Mendelson, an analyst at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said he
was surprised by the number of puzzled queries that arose when the
stock market fell May 17 even though the Commerce Department
reported that the trade deficit shrank to $9.75 billion in March.
   ``In our view,'' he said, ``the message of the tape was simply
that this is a bear market.''
   Added Thom Brown, chairman of the investment policy committee at
Butcher & Singer Inc. in Philadelphia:
   ``Today, as in most earlier bear markets, investors are ignoring
the positive factors on the fundamental front. For example,
earnings for most of the basic industry companies are good and
getting better.
   ``But it doesn't necessarily follow that this strength will be
reflected in stock prices near term.''
   For a precedent of this sort of thing, Brown cited the behavior
of the stock of Bethlehem Steel in 1973 and 1974, when the market
suffered through a long period of disfavor.
   At the end of 1972, when Bethlehem posted earnings of $3.02 a
share and paid $1.20 a share in dividends, the stock stood at about
$30, he recalled.
   At the end of 1974, when the company's earnings climbed to $7.85
a share and the dividend to $2.30, the stock was down to $23.
   ``The lesson here is obvious. During a bull market, surprises in
stock prices are likely to be on the upside. In bear markets, the
reverse is usually the case,'' Brown said.
   With all the woes bear markets may bring, Brown and other
analysts observe, they may also present special opportunities for
long-term investors.
   After all, the ideal time to buy stocks in the past has been
when their prices were depressed, especially when bear markets have
gone to extremes.
   Spotting these special ``buying opportunities'' is no easy
assignment, as most market-watchers readily concede. By the time a
bear market gets close to a bottom, the economic news often looks
so bad that hardly anybody wants even to consider buying stocks.
   Still, one signal many Wall Streeters watch for as a likely
portent that a bear market is ending: When the stock market stops
paying attention to ``bad news,'' or even starts finding ways to
interpret it as positive.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon May 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880528-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 0543EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a w AM-Soviets-Religion Adv30   05-28 0977</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets-Religion, Adv 30,1005</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday AMs, May 30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Seems Ready to Ease Curbs on Russian Orthodox Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev appears to
be moving toward significant easing of restrictions on the Russian
Orthodox Church on its 1,000th anniversary this year, according to
U.S. and Canadian experts on Soviet religious affairs.
   It is unclear, however, whether Gorbachev's new way of dealing
with the Orthodox Church signals substantially improved conditions
for other religious groups in the Soviet Union.
   On Monday, during his summit visit, President Reagan was
scheduled to visit the Danilov Monastery outside Moscow, seat of
the Orthodox Church's patriarchate, ``to symbolize our concern for
religious freedom,'' said White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   Word reached the presidential party late last week in Helsinki,
Finland, that the Soviets had questioned the participation of one
of the religious groups that are to meet with Reagan at the
monastery. Fitzwater said he did not know which religious group
prompted the Soviet objection. The meeting, he said, ``is still on
as far as I know.''
   Reagan recently cited ``the first signs of progress'' toward
religious freedom in the Soviet Union.
   He noted that some religious dissidents have been allowed to
emigrate, some new churches have been organized and Soviet
authorities have announced they will permit the printing of 100,000
Bibles.
   ``These are encouraging signs and we welcome them,'' the
president told a White House conference May 3. ``What we hope for
ultimately is a willingness to see continued change, in the spirit
of glasnost, when it comes to matters of religion.''
   Peter Reddaway, director of the Kennan Institute for Advanced
Russian Studies in Washington, said he is impressed by Gorbachev's
meeting with leaders of the Russian Orthodox Church on April 29 to
appeal for their support.
   Reddaway said it apparently was the first such meeting since
1943, when Stalin conferred with church leaders to help rally the
country against Nazi Germany during World War II.
   Taking part in the most recent Kremlin session were Patriarch
Pimen, head of the Orthodox Church, Metropolitan Filaret of Kiev
and Galitsky and other members of the holy synod, the church's
governing body.
   Gorbachev told them that a new law on ``freedom of conscience''
was being drafted to reflect the ``tangible results of new
approaches to state-church relations in the conditions of
perestroika and democratization.''
   Details of the new law have not been announced.
   Reddaway said there are indications that the new statute will
include removing the ban on the church's involvement in charitable
activities.
   ``If that is indeed the case, then to my mind it's quite a
significant _ and possibly even very significant _ shift in
official policy,'' he said.
   Reddaway said that when he visited Moscow in January, he learned
that the Russian Republic's minister of health had called in
representatives of churches in Moscow and told them ``the time had
come for the churches to exercise their charitable urges.''
   The Soviet official ``proposed that each of them should adopt a
major Moscow hospital and provide basic services to patients in
that hospital. Apparently the church leaders agreed. This is rather
remarkable,'' Reddaway said.
   As for other religious denominations, Reddaway said ``there are
some signs that these still-illegal groups are being tolerated, de
facto, more than in the past _ even the Ukrainian Catholics, who
are the biggest single outlawed church.''
   Unofficial estimates of the number of religious believers in the
Soviet Union put the total at upwards of 90 million people. This
includes 40 million to 50 million adherents of the Russian Orthodox
Church, 10 million Eastern Rite and Roman Catholics; 4 million
Protestants, including Baptists and Pentecostalists; 2 million
Jews, and tens of millions of Moslems.
   Bohdan Bociurkiw, a political science professor at Carleton
University in Ottawa, said church-state relations under Gorbachev
have dramatically improved for the Orthodox Church but have ``not
improved in relationship to most other churches.''
   He said ``the main linkage between the regime and the (Orthodox)
Church is mutual perception of common national interest.''
   ``Gorbachev is courting Russian nationalists, he's courting
believers, but he would not make concessions to churches that he
views as centrifugal _ that would not fit into that notion of
Russian national interest,'' Bociurkiw said. ``It's not a change in
principle, but it's a pragmatic change in policy.''
   Elan Steinberg, executive director of the New York-based World
Jewish Congress, said that for Soviet Jews, ``conditions are better
than they have been in the past, but there is certainly a long way
yet to go.''
   Steinberg said there has been a major increase in the number of
Soviet Jews being allowed to emigrate, from fewer than 1,000 in
1986 to about 10,000 in the past year, and greater access to Jewish
cultural and religious materials.
   He said World Jewish Congress officials recently had ``positive
and constructive'' talks in Moscow with Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze about Soviet Jewry, the Middle East and
East-West relations.
   Kent Hill, director of the Institute on Religion and Democracy,
a Washington-based, non-profit research group, said an estimated
160 religious dissidents remain in Soviet labor camps or internal
exile, a decline of about 150 since January 1986.
   Hill said he sensed a relaxation of government restrictions
during a recent two-week visit to active churches in the Russian
Republic, the Ukraine, Latvia and Estonia, but a wary, skeptical
attitude among many Russian Orthodox and Protestant believers.
   Unlike some Western observers, he said, ``they are far more
cautious in making optimistic projections about the future.''
   ``First of all, they're not at all sure Gorbachev's position is
assured. They don't know how long he's going to be around,'' Hill
said.
   ``Another reason is that in the past they have seen these cycles
of relaxation be followed by renewed repression.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, May 30</NOTE>
