<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, May 30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev, Though Avowed Atheist, Has Invoked Names of Deities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviets-Religion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev may be general secretary
of the avowedly atheistic Soviet Communist Party, but that hasn't
stopped him from referring several times in recent months to God
and Jesus Christ.
   Gorbachev, whose mother is a regular churchgoer, used a biblical
allusion during a May 18 interview with The Washington Post and
Newsweek when seeking to explain the limits on his current drive to
restructure Soviet society.
   ``Jesus Christ alone knew answers to all questions and knew how
to feed 20,000 Jews with five loaves of bread,'' he said. ``We
don't possess that skill, we have no ready prescription to solve
all our problems quickly.''
   Last December, Gorbachev invoked God's name during summit talks
with President Reagan in Washington.
   The Soviet leader said his visit had augmented his knowledge
about the United States.
   ``We discussed with the president that it would be a good thing
to have more of an informal visit, to travel around the country ...
and I believe that if the Politburo and God are well disposed
toward me then I might do this without putting it off for too
long,'' he said.
</TEXT>
