<FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 0556EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Week'sBusiness Adv28-29-2Takes   05-28 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Week's Business, Adv 28-29-2 Takes,0749</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 28-29</NOTE>
<HEAD>Volume Drought Follows Wall Street Deluge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the crash of 1987 recedes into memory, Wall
Streeters are sounding a new lament: The stock market is too quiet.
   Fear of the volatility that rocked the markets last fall and in
early 1988 appears to have created a kind of paralysis, leaving
brokers sitting by idle telephones while their customers watch and
wait.
   By all accounts, the crash frightened away not only individual
investors but also professional managers who work for pensions
funds and other large pools of money.
   In congressional testimony this past week, David Ruder, chairman
of the Securities and Exchange Commission, said institutional money
managers were suffering from ``great fear about volatility.''
   Through May 24, trading volume this year on the New York Stock
Exchange is running 6.4 percent behind its pace in 1987. At the
American Stock Exchange, the dropoff has been 27.1 percent.
   Last Monday, when 102.64 million shares were traded, was the
quietest session not affected by a holiday at the Big Board in
nearly a year and a half.
   The story is much the same in the bond market, where inflation
worries have intensified the post-crash blues. David Resler,
economist at Nomura Securities International, recently calculated
that customer transactions for primary dealers in U.S. government
securities were down 22 percent from their 1987 rate.
   The way many analysts see it, the outlook doesn't look good for
an improvement in this situation any time soon, with the ``dog
days'' of summer approaching.
   ``From now through Labor Day, anyway, it's going to be dull,''
said Raymond F. DeVoe Jr. at Legg Mason Wood Walker Inc.
   In such a climate, morale on Wall Street is naturally low. The
Wall Street Journal reports that one major investment firm, Kidder,
Peabody & Co., is considering putting some of its traders on a
four-day work week this summer, although the firm denies that.
   ``By their very nature, traders want immediate gratification,''
observed William King, head of equity trading at Nikko Securities
International.
   ``In bull markets, there is plenty of that, with abundant
activity and many stories. But bear markets see little activity and
less information.
   ``Traders give up quickly on their positions. That is why we see
such sleepy trading rooms.''
   Viewed from a historical perspective, the numbers might not
appear to warrant so much gloom. Although average volume on the
NYSE reached 188.94 million shares in 1987, it averaged less than
100 million shares a day as recently as 1984. Ten years ago, it was
less than 30 million shares.
   So a casual observer might regard the current slump as no more
than a modest retrenchment after a long period of explosive growth.
   In truth, Wall Streeters, like people in a good many other
businesses, are known for a tendency to hyperbole when they talk
about their problems.
   But analysts also point out that the recent slowdown is a very
real threat to jobs and profits in an industry that had expanded
its staff, facilities, plans and ambitions through the long 1982-87
bull market.
   According to the Labor Department, employment in the securities
industry grew from 243,700 at the end of 1980 to 453,500 seven
years later.
   ``When volume is down and expenses keep rising, firms really get
stung,'' said DeVoe.
   Matthew Drennan, a New York University professor, noted in a
study released this past week that the New York securities industry
had lost 8,000 jobs since the crash and could lose 18,000 more by
the end of this year.
   For the stock market and the investors who participate in it, a
decline in Big Board trading volume has traditionally meant trouble.
   The last time it happened was 1977, when the Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials fell 17 percent in a year generally characterized
as ``mixed.''
   Before that, volume shrank in 1974, 1973, 1969 and 1962, all of
which witnessed significant declines in stock prices.
   The scariest periods for investors may be violent selloffs on
huge volume like the one that occurred last October. But as Newton
Zinder, a veteran analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., put it in
a commentary this week, ``light volume is not a positive sign when
the market is in a declining phase.''
</TEXT>
