<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     05-28 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disposable Income Down, Stock and Bond Markets Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A steep drop in Americans' April disposable income and a
slowdown in consumer spending have not eased investor fears of
higher inflation or dissuaded economists from forecasting higher
growth this year.
   Disposable personal incomes fell 0.9 percent last month, the
largest drop in a year and the first decline in that category since
last November, the Commerce Department reported Friday.
   Economists attributed the decline to higher tax bills, which
also compelled many consumers to resist big purchases last month.
That left spending basically unchanged in April after a 0.8 percent
rise in March.
   Before adjusting for taxes, personal incomes edged up a tiny 0.1
percent in April after a giant 1.1 percent rise in March.
   The weak income growth and stagnant spending figures ordinarily
would be regarded as signs of a slowing economy. But economists
said the April tax payments, along with an early Easter, helped
depress consumer spending, one of the key engines of economic
growth.
   The report was largely ignored by the financial markets, which
have been preoccupied with anxiety over higher inflation and rising
interest rates spawned by other signs of rapid economic growth.
   There is a spreading belief that the Federal Reserve is
tightening credit to slow the economy down.
   Stocks fell on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones average of 30
industrials dropped 10.31 points to 1,956.44, finishing the week
with a net gain of 3.85 points. Volume was light.
   In the bond market, a key barometer of interest-rate trends,
prices ended largely mixed after falling earlier in the day. Many
traders quit early for the long Memorial Day weekend.
   Economists who had worried that the October stock crash foretold
a recession have since expressed surprise at the country's surging
economic growth, as signaled by low unemployment, surging exports
and strains on productive capacities.
   The latest survey of the National Association of Business
Economists released Friday showed a substantial upward revision in
growth estimates for this year compared with a survey done three
months ago.
   The economists, who advise some of the country's largest
corporations, said they were looking for the gross national product
to expand 2.9 percent this year, which would match the performance
turned in during 1986 and 1987.
   On Thursday, the government to revise its own estimate of
overall economic growth to 3.9 percent for the first three months
of the year instead of 2.3 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
